{"title_page": "Jitender Singh Shunty", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jitender Singh Shunty\n| image = Swachh bharat abhiyan Jitender Singh Shunty-dp.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|08|01|df=y}}\n| residence = Vivek Vihar, New Delhi\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| office = \n| term = \n| office1 = Member [[Legislative Assembly of Delhi]]\n| constituency1 = [[Shahdara (Delhi Assembly constituency)]]\n| term1 = 2013-2015\n| office2 = \n| term2 = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = [[BJP]]\n| religion = \n| spouse = Manjeet Kaur Shunty\n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| date = \n| year = \n| source = \n| parents = Late Pritpal Singh\n| awards = 'First Sikh in the world to donate blood 100 times' and the title of 'Donor Singh\u2019 RED & White Bravery Award - 2000 (Social Service), ISBTI- Chapter award for donating blood 70 times, 100 times Blood Donor World Record in World Book of Records, Centurion Award\n}}Jitender Singh 'Shunty' (born  1 August 1962), is an Indian [[politician]] and [[social work]]er. Shunty was elected as the Member of Legislative Assembly from [[Shahdara (Delhi Assembly constituency)|Shahdara]] from Bhartiya Janta Party in 2013.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://delhiassembly.nic.in/aspfile/whos_who/VthAssembly/JitenderSinghShunty.htm|title=Jitender Singh 'Shunty'|website=delhiassembly.nic.in|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nocorruption.in/politician/jitender-shigh-shunty/|title=JITENDER SHIGH SHUNTY MLA of Shahdara Delhi contact address & email|website=nocorruption.in|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ceodelhi.gov.in/OnlineERMS/WriteReadData/Affidavits/U05/SE/62/4-JITENDER%20SINGH%20SHUNTY/4-JITENDER%20SINGH%20SHUNTY.htm|title=General Election 2013 - Candidate's Affidavit AC No. & Name:62 - SHAHDARA|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Jitender Singh Shunty is the founder of Shaheed Bhagat Singh Seva Dal, an NGO that helps to cremate unclaimed bodies and immerse the ashes as guided by the Hindu and Sikh religion.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/photos/2017/02/18/in-photos-claiming-the-unclaimed-corpse-dead-body-cremation-shaheed-bhagat-singh-seva-dal-ngo|title=In Photos: Providing Dignity to the Dead By Claiming the Unclaimed|date=2017-02-18|website=The Quint|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref> The NGO organises blood donation camps and provides blood free of cost to the needy patients. It also provides free ambulance service and works in the field of disaster management.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barnard|first=Catherine|last2=Snell|first2=Jukka|date=September 2017|title=14. Free movement of legal persons and the provision of services|journal=Law Trove|doi=10.1093/he/9780198789130.003.0014|isbn=9780198789130}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/utility/yojanaye/delhi/news/shaheed-bhagat-singh-seva-dal-organized-the-144th-mass-blood-donation-camp-at-leela-ambience-convention-hotel-6041528.html|title=\u0936\u0939\u0940\u0926 \u092d\u0917\u0924 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u0938\u0947\u0935\u093e \u0926\u0932 \u0928\u0947 \u0932\u0940\u0932\u093e \u090f\u092e\u094d\u092c\u093f\u090f\u0902\u0938 \u0915\u0928\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0902\u0936\u0928 \u0939\u094b\u091f\u0932 \u092e\u0947\u0902 144 \u0935\u0947\u0902 \u0935\u093f\u0936\u093e\u0932 \u0930\u0915\u094d\u0924\u0926\u093e\u0928 \u0936\u093f\u0935\u093f\u0930 \u0915\u093e \u0915\u093f\u092f\u093e \u0906\u092f\u094b\u091c\u0928|last=Tyagi|first=Priyadarshni|date=2019-04-01|website=Dainik Bhaskar|language=hi|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n<span class=\"im\"></span>\n\n== Early Life and Career ==\nJitender Singh 'Shunty' was born to Late Pritpal Singh in [[Delhi]]. He was married to Mann kaur 'Shunty'. Jitender founded the Shaheed Bhagat Singh Seva Dal in 1996.<ref name=\":1\" /> He started his career in politics as an independent councillor from Jhilmil ward in Delhi. However, Shunty became a part of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]] in 2008 and contested for the councillor elections from Jhilmil ward of the East municipal corporation and won the elections.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/shunty-had-sought-police-security-a-year-ago-installed-cctv-cameras-at-home/|title=Shunty had sought police security a year ago, installed CCTV cameras at home|date=2014-09-04|website=The Indian Express|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref> Shunty contested his first Delhi Assembly election in 2013,<ref name=\":0\" /> and won from the [[Shahdara (Delhi Assembly constituency)|Shahdara]] constituency with 45,364 votes.<ref name=\":2\" /> Sahil Kashyap<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sahilkashyap.com/about/|title=About|website=Sahil Kashyap - Digital Marketing Strategist {{!}} Branding Expert {{!}} Young Entrepreneur|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> is the founder of Today Headline News<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://todayheadlinenews.com/our-team/|title=Our Team|website=Today Headline News {{!}} THN|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>. He has helped Jitender Singh Shunty and his team in his [[Political campaign|political campaign.]]\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n* In September 2014, Jitender Singh Shunty was shot by an unidentified gunman. Shunty was able to dodge the bullet and remain unharmed. Shunty had been reportedly attacked twice before this in 2013 and 2007.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aajtak.intoday.in/story/firing-on-delhi-bjp-mla-jitendra-singh-shanti-1-778607.html|title=\u0926\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u0940 \u0915\u0947 \u0936\u093e\u0939\u0926\u0930\u093e \u0938\u0947 \u092c\u0940\u091c\u0947\u092a\u0940 \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u092f\u0915 \u091c\u093f\u0924\u0947\u0902\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u092a\u0930 \u092b\u093e\u092f\u0930\u093f\u0902\u0917, \u092c\u093e\u0932-\u092c\u093e\u0932 \u092c\u091a\u0947|website=aajtak.intoday.in|language=hi|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jagran.com/videos/news/national-politicos-condemn-attack-on-bjp-mla-jitender-singh-shunty-v4120.html|title=BJP \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u092f\u0915 \u0936\u0902\u091f\u0940 \u092a\u0930 \u0939\u092e\u0932\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u0928\u0947\u0924\u093e\u0913\u0902 \u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u0928\u093f\u0902\u0926\u093e|date=2014-09-03|website=Dainik Jagran|language=hi|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref> The incident happened at his residence in Vivek Vihar in Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/roSYVtWlAsZKEcLchSln0N/Gunman-opens-fire-at-Delhi-MLA-Jitender-Singh-Shunty.html|title=Gunman opens fire at Delhi MLA Jitender Singh Shunty|last=PTI|date=2014-09-03|website=Mint|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/north/story/caught-on-camera-bjp-mla-jitender-singh-shunty-shot-at-delhi-house-206910-2014-09-03|title=Caught on Camera: BJP MLA Jitender Singh Shunty shot at in Delhi's Vivek Vihar, escapes unhurt|last=DelhiSeptember 3|first=IndiaToday in New|last2=September 3|first2=2014UPDATED|website=India Today|access-date=2019-06-22|last3=Ist|first3=2014 12:32}}</ref>\n* In December 2018, Shunty filed an FIR against actor [[Naseeruddin Shah|Nasiruddin Shah]] for his statement saying that he was worried for the security of his children in India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodtadka.in/entertainment/news/jitender-singh-shunty-file-case-against-naseeruddin-shah-925066|title=\u0938\u092e\u093e\u091c\u0938\u0947\u0935\u0940 \u091c\u093f\u0924\u0947\u0902\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u0936\u0902\u091f\u0940 \u0928\u0947 \u0928\u0938\u0940\u0930\u0942\u0926\u094d\u0926\u0940\u0928 \u0936\u093e\u0939 \u0915\u0947 \u0916\u093f\u0932\u093e\u092b \u0926\u0930\u094d\u091c \u0915\u0930\u0935\u093e\u0908 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u093e\u092f\u0924|website=bollywoodtadka.in|access-date=2019-06-22|date=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n*In December 2018, Shaheed Bhagat Singh Seva Dal led a protest against [[Government of Pakistan]] for Violating Human Rights outside the High Commission of Pakistan in New Delhi<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2018/dec/10/protest-outside-pakistan-high-commission-seeking-protection-of-human-rights-of-sikhs-1909699.html|title=Protest outside Pakistan high commission seeking protection of human rights of Sikhs|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==Award & Achievements==\n\n* <span class=\"s1\"></span>'First Sikh in the world to donate blood 100 times' and the title of 'Donor Singh', awarded by Delhi State Blood Transfusion Council<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/delhi/2019/jun/19/mp-gambhir-felicitates-sikh-social-worker-for-donating-blood-100-times-1992257.html|title=Delhi: MP Gautam Gambhir felicitates Sikh social worker for donating blood 100 times|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>\n* <span class=\"s1\"></span>RED & White Bravery Award - 2000 (Social Service)\n* <span class=\"s1\"></span>A Documentary film made on Jitender Singh Shunty, which was titled \"Angels for the Dead\".  The film received the Gold medal in the Zoie film festival at Georgia\n* ISBTI- Chapter award for donating blood 70 times<ref name=\":0\" />\n*100 times Blood Donor World Record in World Book of Records<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://todayheadlinenews.com/national/donor-singh-jitender-singh-shunty-to-be-conferred-with-world-record-in-delhi/|title=Donor Singh Jitender Singh Shunty to be conferred with world record in Delhi|last=Kashyap|first=Sahil|date=2019-08-20|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n*Centurion Award by The National Blood Transfusion Council (Government of India) & Delhi State Blood Transfusion Council (Govt. of NCT of Delhi)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ismatimes.com/2019/08/donor-singh-jitender-singh-shunty-to-be-conferred-with-world-record/|title=Donor Singh Jitender Singh Shunty to be Conferred with World Record {{!}} ISMA TIMES|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2013 Delhi Legislative Assembly election]]\n* [[Shahdara (Delhi Assembly constituency)]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Members of the Delhi Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jitender Singh Shunty\n| image = Swachh bharat abhiyan Jitender Singh Shunty-dp.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|08|01|df=y}}\n| residence = Vivek Vihar, New Delhi\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| office = \n| term = \n| office1 = Member [[Legislative Assembly of Delhi]]\n| constituency1 = [[Shahdara (Delhi Assembly constituency)]]\n| term1 = 2013-2015\n| office2 = \n| term2 = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = [[BJP]]\n| religion = \n| spouse = Manjeet Kaur Shunty\n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| date = \n| year = \n| source = \n| parents = Late Pritpal Singh\n| awards = 'First Sikh in the world to donate blood 100 times' and the title of 'Donor Singh\u2019 RED & White Bravery Award - 2000 (Social Service), ISBTI- Chapter award for donating blood 70 times, 100 times Blood Donor World Record in World Book of Records, Centurion Award\n}}Jitender Singh 'Shunty' (born  1 August 1962), is an Indian [[politician]] and [[social work]]er. Shunty was elected as the Member of Legislative Assembly from [[Shahdara (Delhi Assembly constituency)|Shahdara]] from Bhartiya Janta Party in 2013.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://delhiassembly.nic.in/aspfile/whos_who/VthAssembly/JitenderSinghShunty.htm|title=Jitender Singh 'Shunty'|website=delhiassembly.nic.in|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nocorruption.in/politician/jitender-shigh-shunty/|title=JITENDER SHIGH SHUNTY MLA of Shahdara Delhi contact address & email|website=nocorruption.in|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ceodelhi.gov.in/OnlineERMS/WriteReadData/Affidavits/U05/SE/62/4-JITENDER%20SINGH%20SHUNTY/4-JITENDER%20SINGH%20SHUNTY.htm|title=General Election 2013 - Candidate's Affidavit AC No. & Name:62 - SHAHDARA|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Jitender Singh Shunty is the founder of Shaheed Bhagat Singh Seva Dal, an NGO that helps to cremate unclaimed bodies and immerse the ashes as guided by the Hindu and Sikh religion.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/photos/2017/02/18/in-photos-claiming-the-unclaimed-corpse-dead-body-cremation-shaheed-bhagat-singh-seva-dal-ngo|title=In Photos: Providing Dignity to the Dead By Claiming the Unclaimed|date=2017-02-18|website=The Quint|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref> The NGO organises blood donation camps and provides blood free of cost to the needy patients. It also provides free ambulance service and works in the field of disaster management.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barnard|first=Catherine|last2=Snell|first2=Jukka|date=September 2017|title=14. Free movement of legal persons and the provision of services|journal=Law Trove|doi=10.1093/he/9780198789130.003.0014|isbn=9780198789130}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/utility/yojanaye/delhi/news/shaheed-bhagat-singh-seva-dal-organized-the-144th-mass-blood-donation-camp-at-leela-ambience-convention-hotel-6041528.html|title=\u0936\u0939\u0940\u0926 \u092d\u0917\u0924 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u0938\u0947\u0935\u093e \u0926\u0932 \u0928\u0947 \u0932\u0940\u0932\u093e \u090f\u092e\u094d\u092c\u093f\u090f\u0902\u0938 \u0915\u0928\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0902\u0936\u0928 \u0939\u094b\u091f\u0932 \u092e\u0947\u0902 144 \u0935\u0947\u0902 \u0935\u093f\u0936\u093e\u0932 \u0930\u0915\u094d\u0924\u0926\u093e\u0928 \u0936\u093f\u0935\u093f\u0930 \u0915\u093e \u0915\u093f\u092f\u093e \u0906\u092f\u094b\u091c\u0928|last=Tyagi|first=Priyadarshni|date=2019-04-01|website=Dainik Bhaskar|language=hi|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n<span class=\"im\"></span>\n\n== Early Life and Career ==\nJitender Singh 'Shunty' was born to Late Pritpal Singh in [[Delhi]]. He was married to Mann kaur 'Shunty'. Jitender founded the Shaheed Bhagat Singh Seva Dal in 1996.<ref name=\":1\" /> He started his career in politics as an independent councillor from Jhilmil ward in Delhi. However, Shunty became a part of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]] in 2008 and contested for the councillor elections from Jhilmil ward of the East municipal corporation and won the elections.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/shunty-had-sought-police-security-a-year-ago-installed-cctv-cameras-at-home/|title=Shunty had sought police security a year ago, installed CCTV cameras at home|date=2014-09-04|website=The Indian Express|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref> Shunty contested his first Delhi Assembly election in 2013,<ref name=\":0\" /> and won from the [[Shahdara (Delhi Assembly constituency)|Shahdara]] constituency with 45,364 votes.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Sahil Kashyap]] the founder of [[Today Headline News]] has helped him and his team in his political campaign.\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n* In September 2014, Jitender Singh Shunty was shot by an unidentified gunman. Shunty was able to dodge the bullet and remain unharmed. Shunty had been reportedly attacked twice before this in 2013 and 2007.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aajtak.intoday.in/story/firing-on-delhi-bjp-mla-jitendra-singh-shanti-1-778607.html|title=\u0926\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u0940 \u0915\u0947 \u0936\u093e\u0939\u0926\u0930\u093e \u0938\u0947 \u092c\u0940\u091c\u0947\u092a\u0940 \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u092f\u0915 \u091c\u093f\u0924\u0947\u0902\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u092a\u0930 \u092b\u093e\u092f\u0930\u093f\u0902\u0917, \u092c\u093e\u0932-\u092c\u093e\u0932 \u092c\u091a\u0947|website=aajtak.intoday.in|language=hi|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jagran.com/videos/news/national-politicos-condemn-attack-on-bjp-mla-jitender-singh-shunty-v4120.html|title=BJP \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u092f\u0915 \u0936\u0902\u091f\u0940 \u092a\u0930 \u0939\u092e\u0932\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u0928\u0947\u0924\u093e\u0913\u0902 \u0928\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u0928\u093f\u0902\u0926\u093e|date=2014-09-03|website=Dainik Jagran|language=hi|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref> The incident happened at his residence in Vivek Vihar in Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/roSYVtWlAsZKEcLchSln0N/Gunman-opens-fire-at-Delhi-MLA-Jitender-Singh-Shunty.html|title=Gunman opens fire at Delhi MLA Jitender Singh Shunty|last=PTI|date=2014-09-03|website=Mint|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/north/story/caught-on-camera-bjp-mla-jitender-singh-shunty-shot-at-delhi-house-206910-2014-09-03|title=Caught on Camera: BJP MLA Jitender Singh Shunty shot at in Delhi's Vivek Vihar, escapes unhurt|last=DelhiSeptember 3|first=IndiaToday in New|last2=September 3|first2=2014UPDATED|website=India Today|access-date=2019-06-22|last3=Ist|first3=2014 12:32}}</ref>\n* In December 2018, Shunty filed an FIR against actor [[Naseeruddin Shah|Nasiruddin Shah]] for his statement saying that he was worried for the security of his children in India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodtadka.in/entertainment/news/jitender-singh-shunty-file-case-against-naseeruddin-shah-925066|title=\u0938\u092e\u093e\u091c\u0938\u0947\u0935\u0940 \u091c\u093f\u0924\u0947\u0902\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u0936\u0902\u091f\u0940 \u0928\u0947 \u0928\u0938\u0940\u0930\u0942\u0926\u094d\u0926\u0940\u0928 \u0936\u093e\u0939 \u0915\u0947 \u0916\u093f\u0932\u093e\u092b \u0926\u0930\u094d\u091c \u0915\u0930\u0935\u093e\u0908 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u093e\u092f\u0924|website=bollywoodtadka.in|access-date=2019-06-22|date=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n*In December 2018, Shaheed Bhagat Singh Seva Dal led a protest against [[Government of Pakistan]] for Violating Human Rights outside the High Commission of Pakistan in New Delhi<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2018/dec/10/protest-outside-pakistan-high-commission-seeking-protection-of-human-rights-of-sikhs-1909699.html|title=Protest outside Pakistan high commission seeking protection of human rights of Sikhs|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==Award & Achievements==\n\n* <span class=\"s1\"></span>'First Sikh in the world to donate blood 100 times' and the title of 'Donor Singh', awarded by Delhi State Blood Transfusion Council<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/delhi/2019/jun/19/mp-gambhir-felicitates-sikh-social-worker-for-donating-blood-100-times-1992257.html|title=Delhi: MP Gautam Gambhir felicitates Sikh social worker for donating blood 100 times|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>\n* <span class=\"s1\"></span>RED & White Bravery Award - 2000 (Social Service)\n* <span class=\"s1\"></span>A Documentary film made on Jitender Singh Shunty, which was titled \"Angels for the Dead\".  The film received the Gold medal in the Zoie film festival at Georgia\n* ISBTI- Chapter award for donating blood 70 times<ref name=\":0\" />\n*100 times Blood Donor World Record in World Book of Records<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://todayheadlinenews.com/national/donor-singh-jitender-singh-shunty-to-be-conferred-with-world-record-in-delhi/|title=Donor Singh Jitender Singh Shunty to be conferred with world record in Delhi|last=Kashyap|first=Sahil|date=2019-08-20|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref>\n*Centurion Award by The National Blood Transfusion Council (Government of India) & Delhi State Blood Transfusion Council (Govt. of NCT of Delhi)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ismatimes.com/2019/08/donor-singh-jitender-singh-shunty-to-be-conferred-with-world-record/|title=Donor Singh Jitender Singh Shunty to be Conferred with World Record {{!}} ISMA TIMES|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2013 Delhi Legislative Assembly election]]\n* [[Shahdara (Delhi Assembly constituency)]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Members of the Delhi Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Thnleo1", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added links with proper references and citations.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jitender_Singh_Shunty"}
{"title_page": "Rosary and scapular", "text_new": "[[File:Mariascapular.jpg|thumb|Statue of the [[BVM(RC)|Virgin Mary]] giving the Scapular to [[St. Simon Stock]] (19th-century) by Alfonso Balzico located in the church of'' [[Santa Maria della Vittoria, Rome]]''|alt=]]\n[[File:Rosary&scapular.jpg|thumb|Rosary and scapular]]\n\nThe exact origins of both the '''rosary and scapular''' are subject to debate among scholars. Pious tradition maintains that both the [[rosary]] and the brown [[Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel]] were given by the Virgin Mary to saints Dominic and Simon Stock respectively during the 13th century.<ref>  [http://www.ewtn.com/library/answers/rosaryhs.htm Saunders, William. \"History of the Rosary\", ''The Arlington Catholic Herald'', October 6, 1994]</ref> Historical records document their growth during the 16th and 17th centuries in Europe. By the early 20th century, they had gained such a strong following among Catholics worldwide that [[Josef Hilgers]], writing in the ''[[Catholic Encyclopedia]]'' of 1914, stated: \"Like the Rosary, the Brown scapular has become the badge of the devout Catholic.\"<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13508b.htm \"Scapular\"], ''The Catholic Encyclopedia'', Vol. 13, New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 22 Dec. 2014.</ref> \n\nSince the Second Vatican Council, the more appropriate term for these items is \"devotional articles\", in order to distinguish them from liturgical actions and items used therewith, such as candles, chrism, or sprinkling with holy water.<ref>Catechism of the Catholic Church \u00a71674</ref> \n\nAs with all religious articles, the use of the [[rosary]] and the [[scapular]] are optional for [[Roman Catholic]]s. Specific [[indulgences]] have been associated with each of them.<ref>Vatican website for Pope Paul VI's [[Apostolic Constitution]] [[Indulgentiarum Doctrina]] [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/paul_vi/apost_constitutions/documents/hf_p-vi_apc_19670101_indulgentiarum-doctrina_en.html]</ref> This article reviews the history, Mariology and the development of the rosary and the scapular as important expressions of popular piety in the [[Roman Catholic Church]].\n\n==Devotions==\n[[File:Glengarriff Church of the Sacred Heart Right East Window St Dominic Receives the Rosary from the Virgin Mary Detail 2009 09 08.jpg|thumb|\"St Dominic Receives the Rosary from the Virgin Mary\", Glengarriff Church of the Sacred Heart]]\nThe rosary and the scapular are viewed as devotional elements of Catholicism. Some historians suggest that the combined effect of the devotional elements and the benefits associated with them made the rosary and the scapular favored among Roman Catholics.<ref>Lea, Henry Charles, 2002,'' A History of Auricular Confession and Indulgences in the Latin Church'', Adamant Media Corp. {{ISBN|1-4021-6108-5}} page 263</ref> However, although many of the faithful choose to pray the rosary and wear the scapular, the linking of the rosary and the scapular is not formally reflected in church doctrine.\n\n==Traditional accounts==\n===St. Dominic=== \n{{Main|Rosary}}\nScholarly debates on the origins of these religious articles are not conclusive. According to the tradition of the Dominicans, the rosary was given to [[Saint Dominic]] in an [[Marian apparition|apparition]] by the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]] in the year 1214 in the church of [[Prouille]], the [[Marian apparition]] receiving the title of [[Our Lady of the Rosary]].<ref name=Beebe/>  However, many scholarly researchers suggests a more gradual and organic development of the rosary, and some attribute it to [[Bl. Alanus de Rupe]].<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13184b.htm Thurston, Herbert, and Andrew Shipman. \"The Rosary.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 13. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 22 Dec. 2014]</ref> Some sources question the authenticity of the apparition to Saint Dominic<ref>Winston-Allen, Anne. ''Stories of the Rose'' Penn State University Press, 1997, {{ISBN|978-0-271-01631-3}} p. 72</ref><ref>Butler, Alban. ''Lives of the Saints'', Forgotten Books, 2007, {{ISBN|1-60506-312-6}} p. 65</ref> but others lend their support.<ref name=Beebe>Beebe, Catherine Beebe, ''St. Dominic and the Rosary'', Ignatius Press, 1996, {{ISBN|0-89870-518-5}}</ref> A key element in the spread of the Rosary in 16th century Rome was the [[Battle of Lepanto (1571)]]. [[Pope Pius V]] requested Catholics to pray the Rosary prior to the battle, held a rosary procession in [[St. Peter's Square]] and then instituted the feast of \"Our Lady of Victory\" to commemorate the victory.<ref>''Calendarium Romanum'', Vatican, 1969, p. 105</ref>\n\nA time-honored Dominican tradition holds that the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]] made [[fifteen rosary promises|fifteen specific promises]] to those who pray the rosary.<ref> Tassone, Susan. ''The Rosary for the Holy Souls in Purgatory'' OSV Press, 2002, {{ISBN|978-1-931709-42-2}} page 163</ref><ref>Geoghegan, G. P., ''A Collection of My Favorite Prayers'', 2006, {{ISBN|978-1-4116-9457-6}}, page 128</ref> The fifteen rosary promises range from protection from misfortune to meriting a high degree of glory in heaven. The 15 promises fall under the category of \"[[private revelation]]\", and as such, are a pious tradition, which a person is free to believe or not believe.<ref>[http://www.olrm.org.au/Fifteen%20Promises.html \"Fifteen Promises of Mary\", Our Lady's Rosary Makers of Australia, Inc.]</ref>\n\n===St. Simon Stock===\n{{Main|Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel}}\n[[File:Virgen del Carmen.JPG|thumb|statue of Our Lady of Mount Carmel, (Chile)]]\n[[Carmelite]] tradition holds that the [[BVM(RC)|Blessed Virgin Mary]] appeared to [[St. Simon Stock]] at [[Cambridge, England]] in 1251 in answer to his appeal for help for his oppressed order and recommended the Brown Scapular to him.<ref>Bunson, Matthew. ''The Catholic Almanac'', 2008, {{ISBN|978-1-59276-441-9}} page 155</ref> Originally, the scapular was a broad band of cloth over the shoulders, serving as an apron, worn still as part of the religious habit by a number of orders of monks and friars. The Brown Scapular has been a key element of Carmelite history since the late 13th century.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/SCRIPTUR/SCAPULAR.TXT Most, William. \"The Brown Scapular\", EWTN]</ref>\n\nLike the purported vision of Mary to St. Dominic, the earliest mention of Simon Stock's vision comes over 100 years later, and there is a lack of documentary evidence that would demonstrate the truth or historicity of the apparition. While Richard Copsey questioned the fact that any apparition took place with respect to the Scapular,<ref>Copsey, Richard. ''Simon Stock and the Scapular Vision'', The Journal of Ecclesiastical History, 50:4:652\u2013683, 1999</ref> Benedict Zimmerman proposed that an apparition did take place in the 13th century, but was to another Carmelite brother, which was later attributed to St. Simon Stock, and that the vision was not of the Virgin Mary, but of a recently deceased Carmelite.<ref>Zimmerman, O.C.D., Benedict. ''The Carmelite Scapular'', \"The Month\", Vol. 150, 1927, pp. 323\u2013237</ref> Over time, the Scapular took an increasingly Marian tone, became identified with Carmelite piety toward The Virgin Mary and the feast of Our Lady of Mount Carmel began to be called the \"scapular feast\". <ref>[http://www.zenit.org/article-23225?l=english Kavanaugh, Kieran. \"Brown Scapular: a 'Silent Devotion'\", ''Zenit'', July 16, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504164642/http://www.zenit.org/article-23225?l=english |date=May 4, 2009 }}</ref> Although the historicity of the scapular vision is rejected, the scapular itself has remained for all Carmelites a sign of Mary's motherly protection and as a personal commitment to follow Jesus in the footsteps of his Mother, the perfect model for all his disciples.\n\nCarmelite tradition has held that, in 1251, the [[Virgin Mary]] made the \"Scapular Promise\" to St. Simon Stock regarding the [[Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel]], namely: \"whoever dies clothed in this habit shall not suffer the fires of Hell.\"<ref name=\"Thomas Petrisko 2000, page 105\">Petrisko, Thomas.''Inside Heaven and Hell'', St. Andrews Press, 2000, {{ISBN|978-1-891903-23-6}} page 105</ref> This is understood to mean that anyone who remains faithful to the Carmelite vocation until death will be granted the grace of final perseverance.<ref name=catechesis>[http://carmelitanacollection.com/catechesis.html Morello, OCD, Sam Anthony and McMahon, O.Carm., Patrick. \"A Catechesis on the Brown Scapular\", ''The Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel: Catechesis and Ritual'', 2000] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109024243/http://carmelitanacollection.com/catechesis.html |date=2016-01-09 }}</ref> The long-standing tradition of the Church has approved the vision of St. Simon Stock as an acceptable cult, but that is distinguishable from authenticating it as a historical experience. \"The question then, from a historical perspective, is not whether Mary appeared to Simon Stock and gave him the scapular, but rather did Simon Stock perceive the Mother of God bestowing this sign of her protection on him and his brothers in Carmel.<ref name=catechesis/> The likelihood is \"probably not\". However, wearing the scapular remains a valuable devotion as a sign of one's commitment to Mary, and a pledge of her protection.\n\nAccording to Christian P. Ceroke: \"The wearing of the Scapular fosters a true devotion to Mary that is based on her supernatural mission in the redemption of mankind. Two Marian doctrines are proposed in the devotion of the Brown Scapular: Mary's Spiritual Maternity and her Mediation of Grace.\"<ref>''The Scapular Devotion'', [[EWTN]], [http://www.ewtn.com/library/mary/scapular.htm]</ref>\n\n==Historical developments==\n{{Scapulars}}\n{{Main|History of the Rosary}}\n===Confraternities===\nThe beginning of the 18th century witnessed a significant growth in Marian confraternities, such as the [[Confraternities of the Rosary]]. A small number of such confraternities had started sometime in the 15th century, through the preaching of Alan de Rupe. Their numbers began to grow under the supervision of the [[Dominican order|Dominican]]s, which also helped create a more uniform format for the Rosary. An important Apostolic Constitution on the Rosary Confraternity was issued by [[Pope Leo XIII]] in 1898.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13188b.htm Thurston, Herbert. \"Confraternity of the Holy Rosary.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 13. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 22 Dec. 2014]</ref>\n\nThe approval of the \"Confraternity of the Scapular\" for every diocese helped the spread of that devotion, reaching its culmination in 1726 via the extension of the [[Feast of Our Lady of Mount Carmel]] (July 16) to the universal Church.<ref>Lea, Henry Charles. ''A History of Auricular Confession and Indulgences in the Latin Church'', 2002, Adamant Media Corp. {{ISBN|1-4021-6108-5}} p. 498</ref><ref>Forster, Mark. ''Catholic Revival in the Age of the Baroque'', 2001, Cambridge Univ Press {{ISBN|0-521-78044-6}} page 145</ref>\n\n===Marian apparitions===\nIn the 19th century, the reported [[Marian apparition]]s of [[Our Lady of Lourdes]] gathered significant attention, and provided momentum for the spread of the Rosary. The spread of the devotion to both the Rosary and the Scapular was influenced by [[Marian apparition]]s of [[Our Lady of F\u00e1tima]] reported by three Portuguese children in 1917.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/MARY/tsfatima.htm de Marchi, John. ''The True Story of Fatima'', Catechetical Guild Educational Society, St. Paul, Minnesota, 1952]</ref> The Fatima messages placed a strong emphasis on the Rosary and in them the Virgin Mary reportedly identified herself as ''The Lady of the Rosary''.<ref>Bunson, Matthew. ''Encyclopedia of Catholic History'', OSV Press, 2004, {{ISBN|978-1-59276-026-8}} p. 348</ref> The visions and messages also encouraged the wearing of the Brown Scapular. In the final F\u00e1tima appearance on October 13, 1917 the Virgin Mary had a brown [[scapular]] in one hand and a [[rosary]] in the other.<ref>Santos, Lucia. ''Fatima in Lucia's Own Words'', Ravengate Press, 1976, {{ISBN|0-911218-10-6}}</ref>\n\n===Associations===\nThe 20th century witnessed the development of a number of Marian organizations. The [[Blue Army of Our Lady of Fatima]] was formed in 1946 in the United States and through \"Scapular Magazine\" helped enroll one million Americans to pray the Rosary based on the F\u00e1tima messages regarding the [[Consecration of Russia]]. The Blue Army eventually reached a larger audience of several million members.<ref>Stravinskas, Peter. ''Catholic Dictionary'', OSV Press 2002, {{ISBN|978-0-87973-390-2}} page 141</ref><ref>Becchio, Bruno. ''Encyclopedia of World Religions'' Foreign Media Books, 2006, {{ISBN|1-60136-000-2}} page 127</ref><ref>Lederhendler, Eli. ''Jews, Catholics, and the Burden of History'' Oxford University Press, 2006, {{ISBN|0-19-530491-8}} page 98</ref>\n\n==Mariology==\n===Papal endorsements===\nLeo XIII dedicated the human race to the [[Sacred Heart of Jesus]]. But in his analysis the re-Christianisation was not possible without Mary. So Leo XIII promoted Marian devotion via ten encyclicals on the Rosary and instituted the Catholic custom of daily rosary prayer during the month of October.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/leo_xiii/encyclicals/documents/hf_l-xiii_enc_01091883_supremi-apostolatus-officio_en.html Vatican website: ''Supremi apostolatus officio'']</ref><ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/leo_xiii/encyclicals/documents/hf_l-xiii_enc_22091891_octobri-mense_en.html Vatican website: ''Octobri mense'']</ref>In 1883 he also created the Feast of ''Queen of the Holy Rosary''.<ref>Remigius Baumer, 1988, ''Marienlexikon'', St. Ottilien, pp.41</ref>\n\n[[Pope John Paul II]] stated that: \"Scapular is essentially a habit which evokes the protection of the Blessed Virgin Mary in this life and in the passage to the fullness of eternal glory.\"<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/2001/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_20010912_en.html  Vatican website, General Audiences]</ref> [[Pope John Paul II]] further stated that he received his own first [[Brown Scapular of Mount Carmel]] at age ten when his Marian devotion was taking shape and he continued to wear it into his papacy.  When he gained consciousness before being operated on to remove the bullet that wounded him in [[St. Peter's Square]] on 13 May 1981 he instructed the doctors not to remove his [[Brown Scapular]] during the operation.<ref>[[Pope John Paul II]], 1996, ''Gift And Mystery'', Doubleday Books {{ISBN|978-0-385-40966-7}} page 28</ref><ref>''Lo Scapolare del Carmelo'' Published by Shalom, 2005\n{{ISBN|88-8404-081-7}} page 6</ref> \n\n===Role of the saints===\nSt. [[Theresa of Avila]], St. [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se of Lisieux]] and St. [[John of the Cross]] were all [[Carmelite]]s and wore the monastic Brown Scapular of [[Our Lady of Mount Carmel]]. St. [[Alphonsus Liguori]] of the [[Redemptorists]] and St. [[John Bosco]] of the [[Salesians]] had a very special devotion to [[Our Lady of Mount Carmel]], and were both buried wearing their Brown Scapulars. St. John Bosco's Brown Scapular was later exhumed in very good condition and is kept as a relic at the [[Basilica of Our Lady Help of Christians, Turin]].<ref>Joan Carroll Cruz, 1984, ''Relics'', OSV Press {{ISBN|978-0-87973-701-6}} page 162</ref>\n\nSaint [[Claude de la Colombi\u00e8re]], the confessor of Saint [[Margaret-Marie Alacoque]], had a strong devotion to the [[Brown Scapular]] and considered it one of the most favorite and effective Marian devotions. He also stated that: \"If a person wants to die in his sins, he will die in his sins, but he will not die wearing the Brown Scapular\".<ref>Claude de la Colombi\u00e8re, 1997, ''Spiritual Direction of St. Claude de la Columbiere'', Ignatius Press {{ISBN|978-0-89870-682-6}}</ref> \n\nSt. [[Louis de Montfort]] is widely known for his promotion of the Rosary. Montfort developed specific [[methods of praying the rosary]] to help the meditative process and emphasized the need for purity of intention, attention and reverence in prayers.<ref>Antoine Nachef, 2000 ''Mary's Pope'' Rowman & Littlefield Press {{ISBN|978-1-58051-077-6}} page 4</ref><ref>Joseph Jaja Rao, 2005, ''The Mystical Experience and Doctrine of St. Louis-Marie Grignion de Montfort'' Ignatius Press {{ISBN|978-88-7839-030-0}} page 7</ref>\n<ref>J. Augustine DiNoia, 1996, ''The love that never ends'' OSV Press {{ISBN|978-0-87973-852-5}} page 136</ref><ref>Tim Parry 2007, ''The Legacy of John Paul II'' Intervarsity Press {{ISBN|978-0-8308-2595-0}} page 109</ref>\n\n==Meditative basis==\n{{Original Research|section|date=December 2014}}\nSaints and popes have emphasized the [[Prayer, meditation and contemplation in Christianity|spiritual and meditative]] benefits of the Rosary and the Scapular. [[Pope Pius XII]] said of the Brown Scapular: \"Let it be your sign of consecration to the [[Immaculate Heart of Mary]]\".<ref>Robert Fox, 2004, ''Prayer Book for Young Catholics'', OSV Press {{ISBN|978-1-59276-098-5}} page 135</ref> And in his encyclical [[Ingruentium Malorum]] on the Rosary Pius XII stated: \"And truly, from the frequent meditation on the Mysteries, the soul little by little and imperceptibly draws and absorbs the virtues they contain, and is wondrously enkindled with a longing for things immortal, and becomes strongly and easily impelled to follow the path which Christ Himself and His Mother have followed.\"<ref>[[Pope Pius XII]] Rosary encyclical [[Ingruentium Malorum]] on the Vatican website [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/pius_xii/encyclicals/documents/hf_p-xii_enc_15091951_ingruentium-malorum_en.html]</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Pope John Paul II]] is best known for his devotion to the Rosary, he stated that he viewed the Scapular as a \"habit\" to orient one's Christian life: \"The sign of the Scapular points to an effective synthesis of Marian spirituality, which nourishes the devotion of believers and makes them sensitive to the Virgin Mother's loving presence in their lives... devotion to her cannot be limited to prayers and tributes in her honor on certain occasions, but must become a \"habit\", that is, a permanent orientation of one's own Christian conduct.\"<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/speeches/2001/documents/hf_jp-ii_spe_20010326_ordine-carmelo_en.html John Paul II Scapular Message at the Vatican website]</ref>\n\nThe wearing of a Scapular has been viewed as ''constant meditation'' by Bishop Leo De Goesbriand: \"Wherever I am, whatever I am doing, Mary never sees me without seeing upon my body an evidence of my devotion to her.\"<ref>L. De Goesbriand 2008, ''Meditations for the Use of the Secular Clergy'' {{ISBN|978-1-4086-8655-3}} page 408</ref>\n\nFrom a venerative viewpoint, Father Etienne Richer points out the Rosary and the Scapular as the key devotions that ''harmonize'' with Catholic Liturgy in the meditative process of the [[BVM(RC)|veneration of the Blessed Virgin Mary]].<ref>Raymond Burke, 2008, ''Mariology: A Guide for Priests, Deacons,seminarians, and Consecrated Persons'', Queenship Publishing {{ISBN|1-57918-355-7}} page 667</ref>\n\n==Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Rosary.jpeg|A simple [[Rosary]]\nFile:Rosari 2.jpg|Various Rosaries with [[Crucifix]]es\nFile:Scapulaire nd mont carmel.jpg|The [[Brown Scapular]] of [[Our Lady of Mount Carmel]]\nFile:SzkaplerzCzerwony2.png|The [[Red Scapular of the Passion]]\n</gallery>\n\n{{Portal| Catholicism }}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Mary and Mariology}}\n* [[Rosary]]\n* [[Scapular]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Rosary}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Garry Wills, 2005, ''The Rosary'', Viking Press, {{ISBN|0-670-03449-5}}\n* Augusta Drane, 1998, ''The Life of St. Dominic'', TAN Books, {{ISBN|0-89555-336-8}}\n* Kevin Johnson, 1999, ''Rosary: Mysteries, Meditations, and the Telling of the Beads'' Pangaeus Press {{ISBN|0-9653660-1-4}}\n* John Paul II, 1999, ''Mysteries of Light, Meditations on the Mysteries of the Rosary'' Ligouri Publications, {{ISBN|0-7648-1060-X}}\n* John Paul II, 2002, ''The Rosary Hour'' Simon and Schuster, {{ISBN|0-7434-7061-3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.ewtn.com/expert/answers/brown_scapular.HTM Donovan, Colin B., \"Brown Scapular - History\", EWTN] \n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160109024243/http://carmelitanacollection.com/catechesis.html Morello, OCD, Sam Anthony and McMahon, O.Carm., Patrick. \"A Catechesis on the Brown Scapular\", ''The Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel: Catechesis and Ritual'', 2000]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosary And Scapular}}\n[[Category:Catholic devotions]]\n[[Category:Catholic Mariology]]\n[[Category:Rosary]]\n[[Category:Scapulars]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Mariascapular.jpg|thumb|Statue of the [[BVM(RC)|''Virgin Mary]] giving the Scapular to [[St. Simon Stock]]'' (19th-century) by Alfonso Balzico located in the church of [[Santa Maria della Vittoria, Rome]]]]\n[[File:Rosary&scapular.jpg|thumb|Rosary and scapular]]\n\nThe exact origins of both the '''rosary and scapular''' are subject to debate among scholars. Pious tradition maintains that both the [[rosary]] and the brown [[Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel]] were given by the Virgin Mary to saints Dominic and Simon Stock respectively during the 13th century.<ref>  [http://www.ewtn.com/library/answers/rosaryhs.htm Saunders, William. \"History of the Rosary\", ''The Arlington Catholic Herald'', October 6, 1994]</ref> Historical records document their growth during the 16th and 17th centuries in Europe. By the early 20th century, they had gained such a strong following among Catholics worldwide that [[Josef Hilgers]], writing in the ''[[Catholic Encyclopedia]]'' of 1914 stated: \"Like the Rosary, the Brown scapular has become the badge of the devout Catholic.\"<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13508b.htm \"Scapular\"], ''The Catholic Encyclopedia'', Vol. 13, New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 22 Dec. 2014.</ref> \n\nSince the Second Vatican Council, the more appropriate term for these items is \"devotional articles\", in order to distinguish them from liturgical actions and items used therewith, such as candles, chrism, or holy water. The sacramental related to them would be the rite of blessing, rather than the object blessed.<ref>Catechism of the Catholic Church \u00a71674</ref> \n\nAs with all religious articles, the use of the [[rosary]] and the [[scapular]] are optional for [[Roman Catholic]]s. Specific [[indulgences]] have been associated with each of them.<ref>Vatican website for Pope Paul VI's [[Apostolic Constitution]] [[Indulgentiarum Doctrina]] [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/paul_vi/apost_constitutions/documents/hf_p-vi_apc_19670101_indulgentiarum-doctrina_en.html]</ref> This article reviews the history, Mariology and the development of the Rosary and the Scapular as important expressions of popular piety in the [[Roman Catholic Church]].\n\n==Devotions==\n[[File:Glengarriff Church of the Sacred Heart Right East Window St Dominic Receives the Rosary from the Virgin Mary Detail 2009 09 08.jpg|thumb|\"St Dominic Receives the Rosary from the Virgin Mary\", Glengarriff Church of the Sacred Heart]]\nThe rosary and the scapular are viewed as devotional elements of Catholicism. Some historians suggest that the combined effect of the devotional elements and the benefits associated with them made the rosary and the scapular favored among Roman Catholics.<ref>Lea, Henry Charles, 2002,'' A History of Auricular Confession and Indulgences in the Latin Church'', Adamant Media Corp. {{ISBN|1-4021-6108-5}} page 263</ref> However, although many of the faithful choose to pray the rosary and wear the scapular, the linking of the rosary and the scapular is not formally reflected in church doctrine.\n\n==Traditional accounts==\n===St. Dominic=== \n{{Main|Rosary}}\nScholarly debates on the origins of these religious articles are not conclusive. According to the tradition of the Dominicans, the rosary was given to [[Saint Dominic]] in an [[Marian apparition|apparition]] by the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]] in the year 1214 in the church of [[Prouille]], the [[Marian apparition]] receiving the title of [[Our Lady of the Rosary]].<ref name=Beebe/>  However, many scholarly researchers suggests a more gradual and organic development of the rosary, and some attribute it to [[Bl. Alanus de Rupe]].<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13184b.htm Thurston, Herbert, and Andrew Shipman. \"The Rosary.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 13. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 22 Dec. 2014]</ref> Some sources question the authenticity of the apparition to Saint Dominic<ref>Winston-Allen, Anne. ''Stories of the Rose'' Penn State University Press, 1997, {{ISBN|978-0-271-01631-3}} p. 72</ref><ref>Butler, Alban. ''Lives of the Saints'', Forgotten Books, 2007, {{ISBN|1-60506-312-6}} p. 65</ref> but others lend their support.<ref name=Beebe>Beebe, Catherine Beebe, ''St. Dominic and the Rosary'', Ignatius Press, 1996, {{ISBN|0-89870-518-5}}</ref> A key element in the spread of the Rosary in 16th century Rome was the [[Battle of Lepanto (1571)]]. [[Pope Pius V]] requested Catholics to pray the Rosary prior to the battle, held a rosary procession in [[St. Peter's Square]] and then instituted the feast of \"Our Lady of Victory\" to commemorate the victory.<ref>''Calendarium Romanum'', Vatican, 1969, p. 105</ref>\n\nA time-honored Dominican tradition holds that the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]] made [[fifteen rosary promises|fifteen specific promises]] to those who pray the rosary.<ref> Tassone, Susan. ''The Rosary for the Holy Souls in Purgatory'' OSV Press, 2002, {{ISBN|978-1-931709-42-2}} page 163</ref><ref>Geoghegan, G. P., ''A Collection of My Favorite Prayers'', 2006, {{ISBN|978-1-4116-9457-6}}, page 128</ref> The fifteen rosary promises range from protection from misfortune to meriting a high degree of glory in heaven. The 15 promises fall under the category of \"[[private revelation]]\", and as such, are a pious tradition, which a person is free to believe or not believe.<ref>[http://www.olrm.org.au/Fifteen%20Promises.html \"Fifteen Promises of Mary\", Our Lady's Rosary Makers of Australia, Inc.]</ref>\n\n===St. Simon Stock===\n{{Main|Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel}}\n[[File:Virgen del Carmen.JPG|thumb|statue of Our Lady of Mount Carmel, (Chile)]]\n[[Carmelite]] tradition holds that the [[BVM(RC)|Blessed Virgin Mary]] appeared to [[St. Simon Stock]] at [[Cambridge, England]] in 1251 in answer to his appeal for help for his oppressed order and recommended the Brown Scapular to him.<ref>Bunson, Matthew. ''The Catholic Almanac'', 2008, {{ISBN|978-1-59276-441-9}} page 155</ref> Originally, the scapular was a broad band of cloth over the shoulders, serving as an apron, worn still as part of the religious habit by a number of orders of monks and friars. The Brown Scapular has been a key element of Carmelite history since the late 13th century.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/SCRIPTUR/SCAPULAR.TXT Most, William. \"The Brown Scapular\", EWTN]</ref>\n\nLike the purported vision of Mary to St. Dominic, the earliest mention of Simon Stock's vision comes over 100 years later, and there is a lack of documentary evidence that would demonstrate the truth or historicity of the apparition. While Richard Copsey questioned the fact that any apparition took place with respect to the Scapular,<ref>Copsey, Richard. ''Simon Stock and the Scapular Vision'', The Journal of Ecclesiastical History, 50:4:652\u2013683, 1999</ref> Benedict Zimmerman proposed that an apparition did take place in the 13th century, but was to another Carmelite brother, which was later attributed to St. Simon Stock, and that the vision was not of the Virgin Mary, but of a recently deceased Carmelite.<ref>Zimmerman, O.C.D., Benedict. ''The Carmelite Scapular'', \"The Month\", Vol. 150, 1927, pp. 323\u2013237</ref> Over time, the Scapular took an increasingly Marian tone, became identified with Carmelite piety toward The Virgin Mary and the feast of Our Lady of Mount Carmel began to be called the \"scapular feast\". <ref>[http://www.zenit.org/article-23225?l=english Kavanaugh, Kieran. \"Brown Scapular: a 'Silent Devotion'\", ''Zenit'', July 16, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504164642/http://www.zenit.org/article-23225?l=english |date=May 4, 2009 }}</ref> Although the historicity of the scapular vision is rejected, the scapular itself has remained for all Carmelites a sign of Mary's motherly protection and as a personal commitment to follow Jesus in the footsteps of his Mother, the perfect model for all his disciples.\n\nCarmelite tradition has held that, in 1251, the [[Virgin Mary]] made the \"Scapular Promise\" to St. Simon Stock regarding the [[Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel]], namely: \"whoever dies clothed in this habit shall not suffer the fires of Hell.\"<ref name=\"Thomas Petrisko 2000, page 105\">Petrisko, Thomas.''Inside Heaven and Hell'', St. Andrews Press, 2000, {{ISBN|978-1-891903-23-6}} page 105</ref> This is understood to mean that anyone who remains faithful to the Carmelite vocation until death will be granted the grace of final perseverance.<ref name=catechesis>[http://carmelitanacollection.com/catechesis.html Morello, OCD, Sam Anthony and McMahon, O.Carm., Patrick. \"A Catechesis on the Brown Scapular\", ''The Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel: Catechesis and Ritual'', 2000] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109024243/http://carmelitanacollection.com/catechesis.html |date=2016-01-09 }}</ref> The long-standing tradition of the Church has approved the vision of St. Simon Stock as an acceptable cult, but that is distinguishable from authenticating it as a historical experience. \"The question then, from a historical perspective, is not whether Mary appeared to Simon Stock and gave him the scapular, but rather did Simon Stock perceive the Mother of God bestowing this sign of her protection on him and his brothers in Carmel.<ref name=catechesis/> The likelihood is \"probably not\". However, wearing the scapular remains a valuable devotion as a sign of one's commitment to Mary, and a pledge of her protection.\n\nAccording to Christian P. Ceroke: \"The wearing of the Scapular fosters a true devotion to Mary that is based on her supernatural mission in the redemption of mankind. Two Marian doctrines are proposed in the devotion of the Brown Scapular: Mary's Spiritual Maternity and her Mediation of Grace.\"<ref>''The Scapular Devotion'', [[EWTN]], [http://www.ewtn.com/library/mary/scapular.htm]</ref>\n\n==Historical developments==\n{{Scapulars}}\n{{Main|History of the Rosary}}\n===Confraternities===\nThe beginning of the 18th century witnessed a significant growth in Marian confraternities, such as the [[Confraternities of the Rosary]]. A small number of such confraternities had started sometime in the 15th century, through the preaching of Alan de Rupe. Their numbers began to grow under the supervision of the [[Dominican order|Dominican]]s, which also helped create a more uniform format for the Rosary. An important Apostolic Constitution on the Rosary Confraternity was issued by [[Pope Leo XIII]] in 1898.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13188b.htm Thurston, Herbert. \"Confraternity of the Holy Rosary.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 13. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 22 Dec. 2014]</ref>\n\nThe approval of the \"Confraternity of the Scapular\" for every diocese helped the spread of that devotion, reaching its culmination in 1726 via the extension of the [[Feast of Our Lady of Mount Carmel]] (July 16) to the universal Church.<ref>Lea, Henry Charles. ''A History of Auricular Confession and Indulgences in the Latin Church'', 2002, Adamant Media Corp. {{ISBN|1-4021-6108-5}} p. 498</ref><ref>Forster, Mark. ''Catholic Revival in the Age of the Baroque'', 2001, Cambridge Univ Press {{ISBN|0-521-78044-6}} page 145</ref>\n\n===Marian apparitions===\nIn the 19th century, the reported [[Marian apparition]]s of [[Our Lady of Lourdes]] gathered significant attention, and provided momentum for the spread of the Rosary. The spread of the devotion to both the Rosary and the Scapular was influenced by [[Marian apparition]]s of [[Our Lady of F\u00e1tima]] reported by three Portuguese children in 1917.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/MARY/tsfatima.htm de Marchi, John. ''The True Story of Fatima'', Catechetical Guild Educational Society, St. Paul, Minnesota, 1952]</ref> The Fatima messages placed a strong emphasis on the Rosary and in them the Virgin Mary reportedly identified herself as ''The Lady of the Rosary''.<ref>Bunson, Matthew. ''Encyclopedia of Catholic History'', OSV Press, 2004, {{ISBN|978-1-59276-026-8}} p. 348</ref> The visions and messages also encouraged the wearing of the Brown Scapular. In the final F\u00e1tima appearance on October 13, 1917 the Virgin Mary had a brown [[scapular]] in one hand and a [[rosary]] in the other.<ref>Santos, Lucia. ''Fatima in Lucia's Own Words'', Ravengate Press, 1976, {{ISBN|0-911218-10-6}}</ref>\n\n===Associations===\nThe 20th century witnessed the development of a number of Marian organizations. The [[Blue Army of Our Lady of Fatima]] was formed in 1946 in the United States and through \"Scapular Magazine\" helped enroll one million Americans to pray the Rosary based on the F\u00e1tima messages regarding the [[Consecration of Russia]]. The Blue Army eventually reached a larger audience of several million members.<ref>Stravinskas, Peter. ''Catholic Dictionary'', OSV Press 2002, {{ISBN|978-0-87973-390-2}} page 141</ref><ref>Becchio, Bruno. ''Encyclopedia of World Religions'' Foreign Media Books, 2006, {{ISBN|1-60136-000-2}} page 127</ref><ref>Lederhendler, Eli. ''Jews, Catholics, and the Burden of History'' Oxford University Press, 2006, {{ISBN|0-19-530491-8}} page 98</ref>\n\n==Mariology==\n===Papal endorsements===\nLeo XIII dedicated the human race to the [[Sacred Heart of Jesus]]. But in his analysis the re-Christianisation was not possible without Mary. So Leo XIII promoted Marian devotion via ten encyclicals on the Rosary and instituted the Catholic custom of daily rosary prayer during the month of October.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/leo_xiii/encyclicals/documents/hf_l-xiii_enc_01091883_supremi-apostolatus-officio_en.html Vatican website: ''Supremi apostolatus officio'']</ref><ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/leo_xiii/encyclicals/documents/hf_l-xiii_enc_22091891_octobri-mense_en.html Vatican website: ''Octobri mense'']</ref>In 1883 he also created the Feast of ''Queen of the Holy Rosary''.<ref>Remigius Baumer, 1988, ''Marienlexikon'', St. Ottilien, pp.41</ref>\n\n[[Pope John Paul II]] stated that: \"Scapular is essentially a habit which evokes the protection of the Blessed Virgin Mary in this life and in the passage to the fullness of eternal glory.\"<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/2001/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_20010912_en.html  Vatican website, General Audiences]</ref> [[Pope John Paul II]] further stated that he received his own first [[Brown Scapular of Mount Carmel]] at age ten when his Marian devotion was taking shape and he continued to wear it into his papacy.  When he gained consciousness before being operated on to remove the bullet that wounded him in [[St. Peter's Square]] on 13 May 1981 he instructed the doctors not to remove his [[Brown Scapular]] during the operation.<ref>[[Pope John Paul II]], 1996, ''Gift And Mystery'', Doubleday Books {{ISBN|978-0-385-40966-7}} page 28</ref><ref>''Lo Scapolare del Carmelo'' Published by Shalom, 2005\n{{ISBN|88-8404-081-7}} page 6</ref> \n\n===Role of the saints===\nSt. [[Theresa of Avila]], St. [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se of Lisieux]] and St. [[John of the Cross]] were all [[Carmelite]]s and wore the monastic Brown Scapular of [[Our Lady of Mount Carmel]]. St. [[Alphonsus Liguori]] of the [[Redemptorists]] and St. [[John Bosco]] of the [[Salesians]] had a very special devotion to [[Our Lady of Mount Carmel]], and were both buried wearing their Brown Scapulars. St. John Bosco's Brown Scapular was later exhumed in very good condition and is kept as a relic at the [[Basilica of Our Lady Help of Christians, Turin]].<ref>Joan Carroll Cruz, 1984, ''Relics'', OSV Press {{ISBN|978-0-87973-701-6}} page 162</ref>\n\nSaint [[Claude de la Colombi\u00e8re]], the confessor of Saint [[Margaret-Marie Alacoque]], had a strong devotion to the [[Brown Scapular]] and considered it one of the most favorite and effective Marian devotions. He also stated that: \"If a person wants to die in his sins, he will die in his sins, but he will not die wearing the Brown Scapular\".<ref>Claude de la Colombi\u00e8re, 1997, ''Spiritual Direction of St. Claude de la Columbiere'', Ignatius Press {{ISBN|978-0-89870-682-6}}</ref> \n\nSt. [[Louis de Montfort]] is widely known for his promotion of the Rosary. Montfort developed specific [[methods of praying the rosary]] to help the meditative process and emphasized the need for purity of intention, attention and reverence in prayers.<ref>Antoine Nachef, 2000 ''Mary's Pope'' Rowman & Littlefield Press {{ISBN|978-1-58051-077-6}} page 4</ref><ref>Joseph Jaja Rao, 2005, ''The Mystical Experience and Doctrine of St. Louis-Marie Grignion de Montfort'' Ignatius Press {{ISBN|978-88-7839-030-0}} page 7</ref>\n<ref>J. Augustine DiNoia, 1996, ''The love that never ends'' OSV Press {{ISBN|978-0-87973-852-5}} page 136</ref><ref>Tim Parry 2007, ''The Legacy of John Paul II'' Intervarsity Press {{ISBN|978-0-8308-2595-0}} page 109</ref>\n\n==Meditative basis==\n{{Original Research|section|date=December 2014}}\nSaints and popes have emphasized the [[Prayer, meditation and contemplation in Christianity|spiritual and meditative]] benefits of the Rosary and the Scapular. [[Pope Pius XII]] said of the Brown Scapular: \"Let it be your sign of consecration to the [[Immaculate Heart of Mary]]\".<ref>Robert Fox, 2004, ''Prayer Book for Young Catholics'', OSV Press {{ISBN|978-1-59276-098-5}} page 135</ref> And in his encyclical [[Ingruentium Malorum]] on the Rosary Pius XII stated: \"And truly, from the frequent meditation on the Mysteries, the soul little by little and imperceptibly draws and absorbs the virtues they contain, and is wondrously enkindled with a longing for things immortal, and becomes strongly and easily impelled to follow the path which Christ Himself and His Mother have followed.\"<ref>[[Pope Pius XII]] Rosary encyclical [[Ingruentium Malorum]] on the Vatican website [https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/pius_xii/encyclicals/documents/hf_p-xii_enc_15091951_ingruentium-malorum_en.html]</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Pope John Paul II]] is best known for his devotion to the Rosary, he stated that he viewed the Scapular as a \"habit\" to orient one's Christian life: \"The sign of the Scapular points to an effective synthesis of Marian spirituality, which nourishes the devotion of believers and makes them sensitive to the Virgin Mother's loving presence in their lives... devotion to her cannot be limited to prayers and tributes in her honor on certain occasions, but must become a \"habit\", that is, a permanent orientation of one's own Christian conduct.\"<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/speeches/2001/documents/hf_jp-ii_spe_20010326_ordine-carmelo_en.html John Paul II Scapular Message at the Vatican website]</ref>\n\nThe wearing of a Scapular has been viewed as ''constant meditation'' by Bishop Leo De Goesbriand: \"Wherever I am, whatever I am doing, Mary never sees me without seeing upon my body an evidence of my devotion to her.\"<ref>L. De Goesbriand 2008, ''Meditations for the Use of the Secular Clergy'' {{ISBN|978-1-4086-8655-3}} page 408</ref>\n\nFrom a venerative viewpoint, Father Etienne Richer points out the Rosary and the Scapular as the key devotions that ''harmonize'' with Catholic Liturgy in the meditative process of the [[BVM(RC)|veneration of the Blessed Virgin Mary]].<ref>Raymond Burke, 2008, ''Mariology: A Guide for Priests, Deacons,seminarians, and Consecrated Persons'', Queenship Publishing {{ISBN|1-57918-355-7}} page 667</ref>\n\n==Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Rosary.jpeg|A simple [[Rosary]]\nFile:Rosari 2.jpg|Various Rosaries with [[Crucifix]]es\nFile:Scapulaire nd mont carmel.jpg|The [[Brown Scapular]] of [[Our Lady of Mount Carmel]]\nFile:SzkaplerzCzerwony2.png|The [[Red Scapular of the Passion]]\n</gallery>\n\n{{Portal| Catholicism }}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Mary and Mariology}}\n* [[Rosary]]\n* [[Scapular]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Rosary}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Garry Wills, 2005, ''The Rosary'', Viking Press, {{ISBN|0-670-03449-5}}\n* Augusta Drane, 1998, ''The Life of St. Dominic'', TAN Books, {{ISBN|0-89555-336-8}}\n* Kevin Johnson, 1999, ''Rosary: Mysteries, Meditations, and the Telling of the Beads'' Pangaeus Press {{ISBN|0-9653660-1-4}}\n* John Paul II, 1999, ''Mysteries of Light, Meditations on the Mysteries of the Rosary'' Ligouri Publications, {{ISBN|0-7648-1060-X}}\n* John Paul II, 2002, ''The Rosary Hour'' Simon and Schuster, {{ISBN|0-7434-7061-3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.ewtn.com/expert/answers/brown_scapular.HTM Donovan, Colin B., \"Brown Scapular - History\", EWTN] \n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160109024243/http://carmelitanacollection.com/catechesis.html Morello, OCD, Sam Anthony and McMahon, O.Carm., Patrick. \"A Catechesis on the Brown Scapular\", ''The Scapular of Our Lady of Mount Carmel: Catechesis and Ritual'', 2000]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosary And Scapular}}\n[[Category:Catholic devotions]]\n[[Category:Catholic Mariology]]\n[[Category:Rosary]]\n[[Category:Scapulars]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosary_and_scapular"}
{"title_page": "Friday Night at the Village Vanguard", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Friday Night at the Village Vanguard\n| type       = live album\n| artist     = [[Art Pepper]]\n| cover      = Friday Night at the Village Vanguard.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1977\n| recorded   = 29 July 1977\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     = 54:12\n| label      = [[Contemporary Records|Contemporary]]/[[Original Jazz Classics|OJC]]\n| producer   = [[Lester Koenig]] & John Koenig\n| prev_title = [[Thursday Night at the Village Vanguard]]\n| prev_year  = 1977\n| next_title = [[Saturday Night at the Village Vanguard]]\n| next_year  = 1977\n}}\n'''''Friday Night at the Village Vanguard''''' is a 1977 [[jazz]] [[album]] by [[saxophonist]] [[Art Pepper]] playing with [[George Cables]], [[George Mraz]] and [[Elvin Jones]].\n\nArt Pepper played at the [[Village Vanguard]] [[jazz]] club in [[New York City]] twice during 1977. The second occasion was recorded and was released as three albums: ''[[Thursday Night at the Village Vanguard]]'', ''Friday Night at the Village Vanguard'' and ''[[Saturday Night at the Village Vanguard]]''. Further tracks appeared on the album ''[[More for Les at the Village Vanguard]]'' and a complete record of Pepper's residency was subsequently released as ''The Complete Village Vanguard Sessions''.\n\nIn the sleeve notes, Pepper says of his own tunes:\n\n<blockquote>\nMy tunes are very difficult to read and interpret. I write down all the parts, and ask my group to play it like it's written for a while and then just use it as a guide and play with their own feelings.\n</blockquote>\n\nOf \"But Beautiful\" he says:\n\n<blockquote>\nBillie Holiday sang this song so beautifully. I've always been influenced by the way a good singer can express something beyond the words of a song. I try to express the quality of the human voice when I'm playing a ballad.\n</blockquote>\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[The Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD]] Fourth Edition, 1998\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3|3}}\n| noprose = yes\n| rev2 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=RSJRG>{{Cite book\n |editor-last=Swenson\n |editor-first=J.\n | author-link = \n | year = 1985\n | title = The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide\n | publisher = Random House/Rolling Stone\n | location = USA\n | isbn = 0-394-72643-X\n | pages = 160\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Las Cuevas de Mario\" ([[Art Pepper]])&nbsp;\u2014 11:08\n#\"[[But Beautiful (song)|But Beautiful]]\" ([[Jimmy Van Heusen]]; [[Johnny Burke (lyricist)|Johnny Burke]])&nbsp;\u2014 10:17\n#\"[[Caravan (1937 song)|Caravan]]\" ([[Duke Ellington|Edward Kennedy Ellington]]; [[Juan Tizol]]; [[Irving Mills]])&nbsp;\u2014 13:29\n#\"Labyrinth\" ([[Art Pepper]])&nbsp;\u2014 12:10\n#\"A Night In Tunisia (Dizzy Gillespie) - 5:45 - CD Bonus Track\n::''(Recorded July 29, 1977.)''\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Art Pepper]]&nbsp;\u2014 [[alto saxophone]]; tenor saxophone on \"Caravan\"\n*[[George Cables]]&nbsp;\u2014 [[piano]]\n*[[George Mraz]]&nbsp;\u2014 [[Double bass|bass]]\n*[[Elvin Jones]]&nbsp;\u2014 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Richard Cook & Brian Morton. ''The Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD'' 4th edition. Penguin, 1998. {{ISBN|0-14-051383-3}}\n\n{{Art Pepper}}\n\n[[Category:Art Pepper live albums]]\n[[Category:1977 live albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at the Village Vanguard]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Friday Night at the Village Vanguard\n| type       = live album\n| artist     = [[Art Pepper]]\n| cover      = Friday Night at the Village Vanguard.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1977\n| recorded   = 29 July 1977\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     = 54:12\n| label      = [[Contemporary Records|Contemporary]]/[[Original Jazz Classics|OJC]]\n| producer   = [[Lester Koenig]] & John Koenig\n| prev_title = [[Thursday Night at the Village Vanguard]]\n| prev_year  = 1977\n| next_title = [[Saturday Night at the Village Vanguard]]\n| next_year  = 1977\n}}\n'''''Friday Night at the Village Vanguard''''' is a 1977 [[jazz]] [[album]] by [[saxophonist]] [[Art Pepper]] playing with [[George Cables]], [[George Mraz]] and [[Elvin Jones]].\n\nArt Pepper played at the [[Village Vanguard]] [[jazz]] club in [[New York City]] twice during 1977. The second occasion was recorded and was released as three albums: ''[[Thursday Night at the Village Vanguard]]'', ''Friday Night at the Village Vanguard'' and ''[[Saturday Night at the Village Vanguard]]''. Further tracks appeared on the album ''[[More for Les At the Village Vanguard]]'' and a complete record of Pepper's residency was subsequently released as ''The Complete Village Vanguard Sessions''.\n\nIn the sleeve notes, Pepper says of his own tunes:\n\n<blockquote>\nMy tunes are very difficult to read and interpret. I write down all the parts, and ask my group to play it like it's written for a while and then just use it as a guide and play with their own feelings.\n</blockquote>\n\nOf \"But Beautiful\" he says:\n\n<blockquote>\nBillie Holiday sang this song so beautifully. I've always been influenced by the way a good singer can express something beyond the words of a song. I try to express the quality of the human voice when I'm playing a ballad.\n</blockquote>\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[The Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD]] Fourth Edition, 1998\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3|3}}\n| noprose = yes\n| rev2 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=RSJRG>{{Cite book\n |editor-last=Swenson\n |editor-first=J.\n | author-link = \n | year = 1985\n | title = The Rolling Stone Jazz Record Guide\n | publisher = Random House/Rolling Stone\n | location = USA\n | isbn = 0-394-72643-X\n | pages = 160\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Las Cuevas de Mario\" ([[Art Pepper]])&nbsp;\u2014 11:08\n#\"[[But Beautiful (song)|But Beautiful]]\" ([[Jimmy Van Heusen]]; [[Johnny Burke (lyricist)|Johnny Burke]])&nbsp;\u2014 10:17\n#\"[[Caravan (1937 song)|Caravan]]\" ([[Duke Ellington|Edward Kennedy Ellington]]; [[Juan Tizol]]; [[Irving Mills]])&nbsp;\u2014 13:29\n#\"Labyrinth\" ([[Art Pepper]])&nbsp;\u2014 12:10\n#\"A Night In Tunisia (Dizzy Gillespie) - 5:45 - CD Bonus Track\n::''(Recorded July 29, 1977.)''\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Art Pepper]]&nbsp;\u2014 [[alto saxophone]]; tenor saxophone on \"Caravan\"\n*[[George Cables]]&nbsp;\u2014 [[piano]]\n*[[George Mraz]]&nbsp;\u2014 [[Double bass|bass]]\n*[[Elvin Jones]]&nbsp;\u2014 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Richard Cook & Brian Morton. ''The Penguin Guide to Jazz on CD'' 4th edition. Penguin, 1998. {{ISBN|0-14-051383-3}}\n\n{{Art Pepper}}\n\n[[Category:Art Pepper live albums]]\n[[Category:1977 live albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at the Village Vanguard]]\n", "name_user": "Lester Mobley", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikilink now correct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friday_Night_at_the_Village_Vanguard"}
{"title_page": "Ahlem Fekih", "text_new": "{{short description|Tunisian actress, model, columnist and internet celebrity}}\n{{infobox person|\n| name               = Ahlem Fekih\n| native_name        = \u0623\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647\n| native_name_lang   = Arabic\n| image              = Ahlem_Fekih_Portrait_2020.png\n| caption            = Ahlem Fekih in 2020\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1997|01|03}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]]\n| nationality        = [[Tunisia]]n\n| occupation         = [[Actor| Actress]], [[internet celebrity|Internet celebrity]]\n}}\n'''Ahlem Fekih''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647}}, born January 3, 1997 in [[Sousse]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://celebrity.tn/ahlem-fekih-wiki/|title=Ahlem Fekih Wiki, Biographie, Age, Taille, Mariage & Informations|date=2019-07-31|website=Celebrity.tn - N\u00b01 Official Stars & People Magazine, Wiki, Biographie & actualit\u00e9s|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> is a [[Tunisia]]n [[Actor|actress]], [[Model (person)|model]], columnist and [[internet celebrity]]  known for her role of Warda in the Tunisian series ''Kesmat Wkhayen''.\n\n== Life ==\nAhlem Fekih  started her career as a model at the age of 15. Fekih began her career at the age of 20 in television. She is known for the role of Warda in the Tunisian sitcom ''Kesmat Wkhayen'' . Ahlem  is a presenter in ''Jeu Dit Tout''<ref>{{Citation|title=Jeu Dit Tout|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11958324/|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> ''on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]'', her experience in TV was by chance after meeting a producer, he helped her to participate in a first casting for the role of ''Sophie'' in ''Awled Moufida'' and the second for ''Kesamt Wkhayen'' in the role of Warda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mosaiquefm.net/fr/tv-ramadan-tunisie/550756/ahlem-fekih-mes-ambitions-passent-avant-l-amour|title=Ahlem Fekih: mes ambitions passent avant l'amour|website=MosaiqueFM|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>{{,}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tounestoday.tn/2019/05/12/%d8%a3%d8%ad%d9%84%d8%a7%d9%85-%d9%81%d9%82%d9%8a%d9%87-%d9%88%d8%b1%d8%af%d8%a9-%d9%81%d9%8a-%d8%b3%d9%84%d8%b3%d9%84%d8%a9-%d9%82%d8%b3%d9%85%d8%a9-%d9%88%d8%ae%d9%8a%d8%a7%d9%86-%d9%85%d9%86/|title=\u0623\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647: \u0648\u0631\u062f\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0633\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0629 \u0642\u0633\u0645\u0629 \u0648\u062e\u064a\u0627\u0646: \u0645\u0646 \u0647\u064a\u061f|date=2019-05-12|website=\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0645|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she is one of the most highly rated influential Tunisian women in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tunivisions.net/36711/la-turquie-un-voyage-qui-sannonce-prometteur-pour-la-jeune-actrice-ahlem-fekih/|title=La Turquie : Un Voyage qui s\u2019annonce prometteur pour la jeune actrice Ahlem Fekih !|date=2020-02-11|website=Tunivisions|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>{{,}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tuniscope.com/article/191577/culture/stars/ahlem-fekih-372311|title=En vid\u00e9o : Ahlem Fekih, la petite \u00e9toile montante de la t\u00e9l\u00e9|last=|first=|date=2019-12-28|website=tuniscope.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nShe considers Fethi Haddaoui, [[Hend Sabry]], Dalila Meftahi and Moez Gdiri as her idols.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tunivisions.net/38815/interview-avec-ahlem-fekih/|title=Interview avec Ahlem Fekih|date=2020-04-07|website=Tunivisions|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><br />\n\n== Personal life ==\nAhlem Fekih grew up and raised in [[Sousse]], [[Tunisia]] and she has two brothers and one sister.<br />\n\n\n== Television ==\n=== TV series ===\n\n*2019 : ''Kesmat Wkhayen'' by [[Sami Fehri]]\n* 2020 : ''Masha'er  (season 2)''\n*2020 : ''Mofida's'' ''(season 5)''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elcinema.com/en/person/2145163/|title=Ahlem Fekih elcinema database|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== TV shows ===\n\n*2019 : ''Omour Jedia'' on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]\n*2019 : ''90 Minutes'' on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]\n* 2019 - 2020 : ''Jeu Dit Tout''  on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]\n*2020 : ''Fekrat Sami Fehri'' on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.assarih.com/a159731-\u0627\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645-\u0627\u0644\u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647-\u062a\u0643\u0634\u0641-\u0639\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0627\u0639\u0628-\u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a-\u063a\u062f\u0631-\u0628\u0647\u0627-\u0648\u062a\u062d\u064a\u0644-\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647\u0627-\u0628\u0639\u062f-\u0627\u064a\u0647\u0627\u0645\u0647\u0627-\u0628\u0627\u0644\u0632\u0648\u0627\u062c-|title=\u0627\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647 \u062a\u0643\u0634\u0641 \u0639\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0627\u0639\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a \u063a\u062f\u0631 \u0628\u0647\u0627 \u0648\u062a\u062d\u064a\u0644 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647\u0627 \u0628\u0639\u062f \u0627\u064a\u0647\u0627\u0645\u0647\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0632\u0648\u0627\u062c|website=www.assarih.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons-inline|Category:Ahlem Fekih}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.ahlemfekih.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|10882958}}\n* {{Instagram|fekih.ahlem}}\n{{Actress-stub}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fekih, Ahlem}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Tunisian female models]]\n[[Category:People from Tunis]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tunisian actress, model, columnist and internet celebrity}}\n{{infobox person|\n| name               = Ahlem Fekih\n| native_name        = \u0623\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647\n| native_name_lang   = Arabic\n| image              = Ahlem_Fekih_Portrait_2020.png\n| caption            = Ahlem Fekih in 2020\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1997|01|03}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]]\n| nationality        = [[Tunisia]]n\n| occupation         = [[Actor| Actress]], [[internet celebrity|Internet celebrity]]\n}}\n'''Ahlem Fekih''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647}}, born January 3, 1997 in [[Sousse]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://celebrity.tn/ahlem-fekih-wiki/|title=Ahlem Fekih Wiki, Biographie, Age, Taille, Mariage & Informations|date=2019-07-31|website=Celebrity.tn - N\u00b01 Official Stars & People Magazine, Wiki, Biographie & actualit\u00e9s|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> is a [[Tunisia]]n [[Actor|actress]], [[Model (person)|model]], columnist and [[internet celebrity]]  known for her role of Warda in the Tunisian series Kesmat Wkhayen.\n\n== Life ==\nAhlem Fekih  started her career as a model at the age of 15. Fekih began her career at the age of 20 in television. She is known for the role of Warda in the Tunisian sitcom ''Kesmat Wkhayen'' . Ahlem  is a presenter in ''Jeu Dit Tout''<ref>{{Citation|title=Jeu Dit Tout|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11958324/|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> ''on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]'', her experience in TV was by chance after meeting a producer, he helped her to participate in a first casting for the role of ''Sophie'' in ''Awled Moufida'' and the second for ''Kesamt Wkhayen'' in the role of Warda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mosaiquefm.net/fr/tv-ramadan-tunisie/550756/ahlem-fekih-mes-ambitions-passent-avant-l-amour|title=Ahlem Fekih: mes ambitions passent avant l'amour|website=MosaiqueFM|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>{{,}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tounestoday.tn/2019/05/12/%d8%a3%d8%ad%d9%84%d8%a7%d9%85-%d9%81%d9%82%d9%8a%d9%87-%d9%88%d8%b1%d8%af%d8%a9-%d9%81%d9%8a-%d8%b3%d9%84%d8%b3%d9%84%d8%a9-%d9%82%d8%b3%d9%85%d8%a9-%d9%88%d8%ae%d9%8a%d8%a7%d9%86-%d9%85%d9%86/|title=\u0623\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647: \u0648\u0631\u062f\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0633\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0629 \u0642\u0633\u0645\u0629 \u0648\u062e\u064a\u0627\u0646: \u0645\u0646 \u0647\u064a\u061f|date=2019-05-12|website=\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0645|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she is one of the most highly rated influential Tunisian women in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tunivisions.net/36711/la-turquie-un-voyage-qui-sannonce-prometteur-pour-la-jeune-actrice-ahlem-fekih/|title=La Turquie : Un Voyage qui s\u2019annonce prometteur pour la jeune actrice Ahlem Fekih !|date=2020-02-11|website=Tunivisions|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>{{,}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tuniscope.com/article/191577/culture/stars/ahlem-fekih-372311|title=En vid\u00e9o : Ahlem Fekih, la petite \u00e9toile montante de la t\u00e9l\u00e9|last=|first=|date=2019-12-28|website=tuniscope.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nShe considers Fethi Haddaoui, [[Hend Sabry]], Dalila Meftahi and Moez Gdiri as her idols.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tunivisions.net/38815/interview-avec-ahlem-fekih/|title=Interview avec Ahlem Fekih|date=2020-04-07|website=Tunivisions|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><br />\n\n== Personal life ==\nAhlem Fekih grew up and raised in [[Sousse]], [[Tunisia]] and she has two brothers and one sister.<br />\n\n\n== Television ==\n=== TV series ===\n\n*2019 : ''Kesmat Wkhayen'' by [[Sami Fehri]]\n* 2020 : ''Masha'er  (season 2)''\n*2020 : ''Mofida's'' ''(season 5)''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elcinema.com/en/person/2145163/|title=Ahlem Fekih elcinema database|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== TV shows ===\n\n*2019 : ''Omour Jedia'' on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]\n*2019 : ''90 Minutes'' on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]\n* 2019 - 2020 : ''Jeu Dit Tout''  on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]\n*2020 : ''Fekrat Sami Fehri'' on [[El Hiwar El Tounsi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.assarih.com/a159731-\u0627\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645-\u0627\u0644\u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647-\u062a\u0643\u0634\u0641-\u0639\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0627\u0639\u0628-\u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a-\u063a\u062f\u0631-\u0628\u0647\u0627-\u0648\u062a\u062d\u064a\u0644-\u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647\u0627-\u0628\u0639\u062f-\u0627\u064a\u0647\u0627\u0645\u0647\u0627-\u0628\u0627\u0644\u0632\u0648\u0627\u062c-|title=\u0627\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0642\u064a\u0647 \u062a\u0643\u0634\u0641 \u0639\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0627\u0639\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a \u063a\u062f\u0631 \u0628\u0647\u0627 \u0648\u062a\u062d\u064a\u0644 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647\u0627 \u0628\u0639\u062f \u0627\u064a\u0647\u0627\u0645\u0647\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0632\u0648\u0627\u062c|website=www.assarih.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commons-inline|Category:Ahlem Fekih}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.ahlemfekih.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|10882958}}\n* {{Instagram|fekih.ahlem}}\n{{Actress-stub}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fekih, Ahlem}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Tunisian female models]]\n[[Category:People from Tunis]]\n", "name_user": "Salah Almhamdi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added italics to: Kesmat Wkhayen", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ahlem_Fekih"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United Arab Emirates.svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in the United Arab Emirates (as of 10 February)<br />{{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}\n| map2            = \n| legend 2        = \n| map3            = \n| legend 3        = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Dubai]]<br /> [[Abu Dhabi]]<br />[[Sharjah]]\n| first_case      = [[Dubai]]\n| arrival_date    = 29 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=29|year 1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  = 588<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d>{{cite news |last=Sebugwaawo  |first=Ismail|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-reports-376-new-coronavirus-cases170-recoveries|title=Covid-19: UAE reports 376 new coronavirus cases, 170 recoveries|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=Khaleej Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 20<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| confirmed_cases = 3,736 (as of 11 April)<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| active_cases    = 3,128<ref name=\"stat.\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 CORONAVIRUS PANDEMIC |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |website=Worldometers |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| severe_cases    = 1<ref name=\"stat.\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| fatality_rate   = 0.007%\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://covid19.ncema.gov.ae/en}}\n}}\n\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[United Arab Emirates]] was announced on 29 January 2020. It was the first country in the [[Middle East]] to report a confirmed case.<ref>Turak, Natasha (29 January 2020). [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/29/first-middle-east-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-the-uae.html First Middle East cases of coronavirus confirmed in the UAE] ''CNBC.com.'' Retrieved 19 March 2020.</ref> The first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released on 9 February after recovering. The first two deaths were confirmed on March 20. On 22 March, [[Dubai]] started an 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus. Night curfew was imposed 4 days later while the country began disinfection. School closure was first announced on April 8 for 4 weeks. 3 weeks later, it was announced that school will be closed until the end of the academic year.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases chart}}\n\n===January 2020===\nOn 23 January, [[Abu Dhabi International Airport]] and [[Dubai International Airport]] announced that travelers arriving directly from China would have their temperatures screened.<ref name=\"Khaleej23Jan2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/uae/dubai/china-coronavirus-outbreak-dubai-to-screen-passengers|title=China coronavirus outbreak: Dubai to screen passengers|last=Reuters|date=23 January 2020|website=Khaleej Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/abu-dhabi-and-dubai-airports-to-screen-passengers-for-china-coronavirus-1.968492|title=Abu Dhabi and Dubai airports to screen passengers for China coronavirus|last=Kamel|first=Deena|date=23 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January, the first case in the UAE was confirmed to be a 73-year-old Chinese woman who came to the country on holiday with her family from Wuhan.<ref name=\"first case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hammond|first=Ashley|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-how-the-first-coronavirus-case-in-uae-was-cured-1.1581323524356|title=Watch: How the first coronavirus case in UAE was cured|date=10 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Chaudhary|first2=Suchitra Bajpai|last3=Hilotin|first3=Jay}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|title=Coronavirus in UAE: Four of a family infected|last=Nandkeolyar|first=Karishma|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129111625/https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The family of four, 36-year-old mother,<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" /> 38-year-old father,<ref name=\":0\" /> 10-year-old child,<ref name=\":0\" /> and the 73-year-old grandmother arrived in the Emirates on 16 January and took the grandmother to a doctor with flu-like symptoms on 23 January, where it was discovered that the family was infected.<ref name=\"Infected family UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|title=Coronavirus: UAE records first case|last=Duncan|first=Gillian|date=29 January 2020|work=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Gautam|first2=Shuchita|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129110532/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|archive-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> The announcement led to a sell out of face masks across the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|title=Coronavirus: face masks sell out across the UAE|last=Gautam|first=Shuchita|date=29 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129143403/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|title=Coronavirus: Most pharmacies in the UAE run out of face mask as residents rush to take protective measures|last=Ahmed|first=Ashfaq|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129140304/https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the fifth case of coronavirus in the UAE was confirmed, in someone who had travelled from Wuhan to Dubai.<ref name=\"fifth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|title=UAE announces new coronavirus case|website=The National|access-date=2020-02-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201185052/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref> The Dubai Health Authority (DHA) directed all DHA-licensed hospitals to consider all suspected and confirmed cases as emergencies and patients are to be treated free of charge, including those without insurance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|title=Coronavirus cases in UAE to be treated free of cost, insurance not necessary|first=Dhanusha|last=Gokulan|website=Khaleej Times|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206184719/https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|archive-date=2020-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 8 February, the sixth and seventh cases, of Chinese and a 43-year-old [[Filipino nationality|Filipino]], were confirmed.<ref name=\"sixth and seventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/2-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-1.1581134995319|title=2 new cases of coronavirus in UAE|date=8 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/chinese-filipino-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-in-uae-bringing-total-cases-to-7-1.1581142731007|title=Chinese, Filipino diagnosed with coronavirus in UAE, bringing total cases to 7|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|date=8 February 2020|website=Gulf News |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"seventh case UAE\">{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |title=Condition of Filipino coronavirus patient in UAE 'not improving', says diplomat |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/condition-of-filipino-coronavirus-patient-in-uae-not-improving-says-diplomat-1.69834108 |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February, the first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released after recovering.<ref name=\"first discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Abueish|first=Tamara|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/02/09/Woman-infected-with-coronavirus-cured-UAE-.html|title=Woman infected with coronavirus cured: UAE|date=9 February 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the eighth case was confirmed to be an Indian expatriate who had interacted with a recently diagnosed person.<ref name=\"eighth case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/indian-expat-in-uae-found-infected-by-coronavirus-1.1581392108339?slide=2|title=Indian expat in UAE found infected by coronavirus|date=11 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, two more patients recovered and were discharged from the hospital. The two patients were a 41-year-old Chinese father and his eight-year-old boy.<ref name=\"second discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/uae-announces-recovery-of-two-new-coronavirus-patients-1.1581704777547|title=UAE announces recovery of two new coronavirus patients|date=14 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, the ninth case was confirmed to be a 37-year old Chinese man.<ref name=\"ninth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-ninth-case-of-coronavirus-1.1581869353798|title=UAE announces ninth case of coronavirus|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, the tenth and eleventh case were confirmed to be a 34-year-old Filipino national and a 39-year-old Bangladeshi national who had contact with a Chinese national who had been diagnosed with the virus.<ref name=\"tenth and eleventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKBN20F28J|title=UAE records two new coronavirus cases, total number reaches 11|date=2020-02-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the government announced that two more people, a 70-year old Iranian visitor and his 64-year-old wife, have been diagnosed, taking the total to thirteen.<ref name=\"twelfth and thirteenth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/iranian-couple-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-uae-taking-number-of-cases-to-13-1.69875492|title=Iranian couple diagnosed with COVID-19 in UAE, taking number of cases to 13|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, six more new cases were announced, including four Iranians, one Bahraini and one Chinese national.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/six-new-cases-of-coronavirus-reported-in-uae-1.1582821151401|title=Six new cases of coronavirus reported in UAE|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that case 2, of the 36-year-old Chinese woman, and another 37-year-old Chinese person were discharged after recovering.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" />\n\nOn 28 February, two Italian technicians visiting the country to participate in the [[2020 UAE Tour|UAE Tour]], a top level cycling race, were tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-tour-cancelled-and-dozens-quarantined-as-two-participants-test-positive-1.985664|title=Coronavirus: UAE Tour cancelled and dozens quarantined as two participants test positive|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> 612 people involved in the UAE Tour were quarantined in the homes and the W Abu Dhabi hotel and the Crowne Plaza Abu Dhabi hotel, both in Yas Island, and the two hotels were put on lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aarons|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/27/chris-froome-facing-coronavirus-test-after-uae-tour-is-cancelled|title=Chris Froome facing coronavirus test after UAE Tour is cancelled|date=2020-02-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKCN20M1UW|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two Gulf hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en}}</ref> The 612 people were all screened and the results were negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/21-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-ministry|title=21 confirmed cases of coronavirus in UAE: Ministry|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/news/2020/02/28/cyclists-await-test-results-after-coronavirus-hits-uae-tour|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two UAE hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|website=www.gulf today.ae|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 1 March, six more people tested positive for the coronavirus in the UAE, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of infected persons to 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-six-more-cases-of-covid-19-1.987661|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces six more cases of Covid-19|website=thenational.ae}}</ref> The patients include two Russians, two Italians, a German and a Colombian citizen, who had been in contact with two Italian participants of the UAE Tour who tested positive for coronavirus at the weekend.\n\nOn 3 March, a 16-year-old female Indian student in Dubai tested positive for the coronavirus after  contracting it from her parent who came back after traveling abroad. The parent developed symptoms five days after returning to Dubai. Both the student and her family were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-dubai-school-pupil-tests-positive-for-covid-19-1.988293|title=Coronavirus: Dubai school pupil tests positive for Covid-19|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> On 5 March, the Ministry of Health and Prevention confirmed that a 17-year-old male Emirati student has tested positive for coronavirus and showed no symptoms of it. The student is now stable and is receiving necessary healthcare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-confirms-new-coronavirus-case-1.1583440148424|title=New 30th coronavirus case confirmed on student|website=Gulf News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, two Chinese patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the UAE to seven.<ref name=\"official numbers1\">{{cite news|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829181|title= UAE announces recovery of two cases of COVID-19|work=wam|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The two recoveries, a  38-year-old father and his 10-year-old child, were from the first family to contract the virus, and all members of the Chinese family are now virus-free.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/15-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-the-uae-2-chinese-patients-recover-1.1583547467978|title=15 new cases of coronavirus in the UAE, 2 Chinese patients recover|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that 15 cases of different nationalities have tested positive for the virus, taking to 45 the total infections in the country.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> 13 cases consisted of one individual each from Thailand, China, Morocco and India, two individuals each from Saudi Arabia, Ethiopia, Iran and three individuals from the UAE were detected through early reporting by individuals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khalid|first=Tuqa|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/07/UAE-confirms-15-new-coronavirus-cases-bringing-total-up-to-44.html|title=UAE confirms 15 new coronavirus cases bringing total up to 45|date=7 March 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> All these cases arrived from abroad.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> Two cases, each from the UAE and Egypt, have been diagnosed with the virus by active surveillance system for being in close contact with confirmed cases announced previously in connection with the UAE Tour.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" />\n\nOn 9 March, the UAE recorded 14 new cases, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of reported cases to 59. In a statement, the health ministry said the cases involve four Emiratis, three Italians, two Bangladeshis, two Nepalese, a Russian, an Indian and a Syrian national.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health ministry reports 14 new coronavirus cases |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829607 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-14-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1583753297673|title=14 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|access-date=9 March 2020 |work=Gulf News|date=9 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that two Emiratis, two Ethiopians and a Thai national recovered from the virus, bringing to 12 the total recovered cases in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Five more coronavirus patients recover in UAE: Health Ministry |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829635 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the UAE Ministry of Health and Prevention on Tuesday confirmed 15 new cases, bringing the total number of infected people in the country to 74. The 15 cases involve three Italians, two Emiratis, two from UK, two from Sri Lanka, two Indians, a German, a South African, a Tanzanian and an Iranian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-15-new-cases-announced|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 15 new cases announced|last=Wam|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that five cases recovered, consisting for three Emiratis, one Egyptian and one Moroccan.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ar:5 \u062d\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0634\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u0625\u0636\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u0635\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u062c\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 |url=https://www.wam.ae/ar/details/1395302829848 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=10 March 2020|language=ar|trans-title=Five additional recovery cases from the Coronavirus in the country}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, 11 new cases were announced, bring the total number of cases in the UAE to 85.<ref>{{cite news|last=Salman|first=Nour|url=https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830309|title=11 new COVID-19 cases in UAE: MoHAP|date=12 March 2020|work=Wam|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The individuals were placed under quarantine as suspected cases subsequent to their entry into the UAE and following required testing and monitoring, the individuals were confirmed to be positive. The 11 individuals diagnosed include two Italians, two Filipinos, one Montenegrin, one Canadian, one German, one Pakistani, one Emirati, one Russian and one British citizen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-uae-confirms-11-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 11 new cases of Covid-19|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that a Bangladeshi, a Chinese, and an Italian person recovered from the virus, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the country to 20.<ref name=\"recoveries2\">{{cite news |last=Alfaham |first= Tariq |title= Three more people recover from coronavirus in UAE |url= https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830394 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, 12 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 98. The patients are three Indians, and one each from the UAE, the Philippines, South Africa, Australia, China, Lebanon, the UK, Italy, and Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-confirms-12-new-cases-1.992864|title=12 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> \nOn the same day, 3 people have recovered from the virus bringing the total number to 26, the people are two Emiratis and an Indian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-three-more-recover-in-the-uae-1.992496|title= 3 new COVID-19 recoveries in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> On 18 March, 15 new cases were announced, with the total number of infected people to 113. Patients are from Kyrgyzstan, Serbia, Italy, Netherlands, Australia, Germany, USA, Greece, Russia, Ukraine, Bangladesh, Britain, and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-15-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.994024|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 15 new cases of Covid-19|website=The National}}</ref> On 19 March, UAE confirmed 27 new cases of the novel coronavirus on Thursday along with 30 recoveries in total.\nThe total number of COVID-19 cases in UAE stands at 140, Ministry of Health and Prevention said today in a press conference. Dr. Farida Al Hosani, Director of Communicable Diseases Department at the Health Department said the total number of cases have reached 140. She said five more cases have recovered including three Emiratis, one Syrian and one Sri Lankan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-27-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 27 new cases confirmed|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 20 March, the first two deaths were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-emirates-tally/uae-announces-first-two-deaths-from-coronavirus-wam-idUSKBN2173JU|title=UAE Announces First Two Deaths From Coronavirus: WAM|website=Reuters|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, The Ministry of Health and Prevention made the announcement. One of the two cases is 78-year old Arab national who came from Europe and tested positive for COVID-19 and died due to heart attack while the other is a 59-year-old Asian expat who was suffering from chronic diseases including heart disease and kidney failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/uae-announces-2-coronavirus-deaths-1.1584735850926|title=UAE announces 2 coronavirus deaths|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, there were seven recovery cases, but however, there were 13 new cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-13-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-1|title=Covid-19 in UAE: 13 new cases, seven recoveries confirmed|first=Web|last=Report|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] announced that it will be suspending all passenger flights effective March 25 in response to the coronavirus, but will continue to operate cargo flights for essential goods.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://apnews.com/10aa229f979a05241ede3c349f5e4d2d | title=Dubai's Emirates cuts passenger flights to 13 destinations| date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[UAE]] announces 45 new coronavirus cases. Total cases reported in the country are now 198.<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-45-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1584969735068|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 45 new coronavirus cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government urged people to stay in their homes and only leave home for an emergency or for work, said Ministry of Interior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-urges-people-to-stay-in-their-homes-1.1584916668613|title=Coronavirus: UAE urges people to stay in their homes|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government shut malls for two weeks. Fish, meat and vegetable markets also closed for a renewable period of two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-shuts-malls-for-two-weeks-1.1584914600541|title=Coronavirus: UAE shuts malls for two weeks|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government also suspended all passenger and transit flights. The suspension of flights will commence at 23:59 (UAE local time) on Wednesday 25 March and will last for an initial 14 days, subject to further directives by the relevant authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/aviation/coronavirus-uae-suspends-all-passenger-and-transit-flights-1.1584917287850|title=Coronavirus: UAE suspends all passenger and transit flights|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Telecommunications Regulatory Authority (UAE)|TRA]] unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid the coronavirus outbreak. The TRA explained that residents will now be able to use Microsoft Teams, Zoom and Blackboard, which are available on all networks in the country. Microsoft Skype for Business and Google Hangouts are compatible with fixed Internet networks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-tra-unblocks-skype-for-business-google-hangouts-amid-covid-19-outbreak-1.1585047632245|title=UAE: TRA unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid COVID-19 outbreak|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> Four new recovery cases and 50 new cases were confirmed. These new cases were among individuals who had close contact with cases announced previously, as well as people who returned from abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-50-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 50 new cases confirmed|website= www.khaleejtimes.com/}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, UAE announces 85 new cases, the total number of infections in the country reaches 333, with seven recoveries reported on Wednesday, March 25. The announcement was made during a regular media briefing held Wednesday, March 25 by Farida Al Hosani, official spokesperson of the UAE health sector. Seven people were recovered making the total recoveries in the UAE 52.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-announces-85-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585141534235|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 85 new COVID-19 cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, 64 people were arrested for breaking home quarantine after they came in direct contact with people infected with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/crime/coronavirus-uae-arrests-64-for-breaking-home-quarantine-law-1.1585155529277|title=Coronavirus: UAE arrests 64 for breaking home quarantine law|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, UAE 72 new cases and three recoveries were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-reports-72-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585331041900|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 72 new corona virus cases|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, UAE on Saturday announced 63 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total of confirmed cases to 468.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-63-new-cases-of-covid-19-on-saturday-1.1585401355346 |title = Coronavirus: UAE: 63 new cases of COVID-19 on Saturday}}</ref> On 29 March, UAE the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 102 new cases, taking the total cases in the country to 570. The 102 new cases patients consisted of one person from New Zealand, Slovakia, Morocco, Greece, China, France, Germany, Algeria, Iraq, Colombia, Venezuela, and Poland. Two people from Brazil, Sweden, Australia, Ethiopia, Canada, Lebanon, Sudan, Saudi Arabia, and Portugal. Three people from Italy and Ireland. Six people from Egypt. Seven people from the UAE and the Philippines. 16 people from Britain. 30 people from India. On the same day, the three new recoveries were announced takes the total tally of recoveries to 58, and another person died from the virus, taking the toll to three in UAE, until March 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-102-new-cases-announced-3-recoveries|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 102 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, UAE announced 41 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total number of confirmed cases in the country to 611. All are in stable condition except two, who are in critical condition. Two more deaths have been announced as well. The total death toll is now five. Three recoveries have also been announced - two Indians and one Filipino.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-41-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1585573506275|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 41 new corona virus cases|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 31 March, UAE The Ministry of Health and Prevention in the UAE has announced 53 new confirmed cases of the coronavirus and one death. The total cases reported in the country is now 664. One death has also been announced, taking the total toll to six. The new cases include one each from Algeria, Lebanon, Pakistan, Iran, Kuwait, Switzerland, Turkey, the Philippines, Italy, France, America and two people from Egypt, Nepal, three people from Britain, four people from the UAE, and as many as 31 people from India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-reports-53-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1585660904284|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 53 new corona virus cases|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Moreover, Al Ras area, one of the city's densely populated areas that's home to the gold souk and museums, was placed under lock down for two weeks starting 31 March preventing all residents from leaving or entering the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/dubai-locks-down-historic-neighborhood-to-prevent-virus-spread|title=Dubai Locks Down Historic Neighborhood to Prevent Virus Spread|last=Elbahrawy|first=Farah|date=31 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 150 new coronavirus cases for a total of 814, with a total number of eight deaths from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-150-new-cases-1|title=COVID-19: UAE confirms 150 new cases, two deaths|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 210 new cases for a total number of cases to 1,024, with 96 recoveries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302834594|title=COVID-19: Ministry of Health announces 210 new cases of COVID-19, 35 recoveries among various nationalities|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, 240 new cases were announced for a total of 1,264, with 108 having fully recovered, and one patient having died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-confirms-240-new-cases-on-friday |title= Covid-19: One expat dead, 240 new cases in UAE |website= Khaleej Times \\accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported another 241 new coronavirus cases, bringing the total number of COVID-19 patients to 1,505.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/covid-19-241-new-coronavirus-cases-reported-in-uae-on-saturday-1.1586001691620 |title=COVID-19: 1 death, 241 new coronavirus cases reported in UAE on Saturday  |website=gulfnews.com |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported 294 new cases of the COVID-19 coronavirus, taking the total number of cases in the country to 1,799. MoHAP also announced 19 new recoveries, taking the total number of recoveries to 144.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-294-new-cases-of-covid-19 |title= Coronavirus: UAE confirms 294 new cases, 19 recoveries |website=Khaleej Times |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported another 277 new coronavirus cases of different nationalities, bringing the total number of cases of infection to 2076, with 11 deaths from the virus, and a total of 167 recovered patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-277-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1586170041645 |title=COVID-19: UAE announces 277 new coronavirus cases, one death |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, The Ministry of Health and Community Protection announced it was monitoring 283 new cases of coronavirus, bringing the number of diagnosed cases to 2359. The Ministry also announced the total of the cases of recovery to 186, with a total number of 12 deaths due to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-283-new-cases-april-7-1- | title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 283 new cases of COVID-19 |website=Khaleej Times |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 300 new cases and 53 new recoveries were announced, with the total number of cases standing at 2,659, with 239 recoveries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-announces-300-new-cases-of-coronavirus |title=Covid-19: UAE announces 300 new cases of coronavirus - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, there were 331 new coronavirus cases and two deaths, with a total of 14 deaths.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/Covid-19-in-UAE-331-new-cases-29-recoveries-announced|title=Covid-19: The UAE reported 331 new coronavirus cases - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, there were 370 new confirmed cases, for a total of 3,360. 150 patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases to 418. There were two deaths from the virus, for a total of 16.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-370-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1586541879415|title=Covid-19: UAE announces 370 new coronavirus cases, two deaths - News |publisher=Gulf News|date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, there were 376 new cases of coronavirus, for a total of 3,736. The total number of recoveries rose to 588. Four patients died of the virus, bringing the total number of deaths to 20.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-reports-376-new-coronavirus-cases170-recoveries|title=Covid-19: UAE reports 376 new coronavirus cases, 170 recoveries - News |publisher=Khaleej Times|date= |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nOn 22 March, [[Dubai]] started a 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |last2=Nasrallah |first2=Tawfiq |title=Watch: Dubai starts massive coronavirus sterilisation drive |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-dubai-starts-massive-coronavirus-sterilisation-drive-1.70524415 |access-date=2020-03-20 |work=Gulf News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, the country imposed night curfew as disinfection in the country began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-uae-imposes-overnight-curfew-disinfection-campaign|title=Coronavirus: UAE imposes night curfew as it carries out disinfection campaign|website=Middle East Eye|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, Dubai lifted their ban on trucks weighting 2.5 tonnes.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://gulfnews.com/amp/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubai-temporarily-lifts-ban-on-movement-of-trucks-1.70618893 |title=Coronavirus: Dubai temporarily lifts ban on movement of trucks |publisher=Gulfnews.com |date=2020-03-25 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 28 March, the country announced that curfews and disinfection would be extended until April 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/443885-uae-extends-sterilisation-programme-until-april-5|title=UAE extends nationwide coronavirus disinfection programme, curfews until April 5|website=ArabianBusiness.com|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Abu Dhabi]] crown prince [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan|Mohammed bin Zayed]] announced that a new testing site has opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/28/UAE-launches-mobile-drive-through-coronavirus-test-center |title=UAE launches mobile drive-through coronavirus test center |publisher=Al Arabiya English |date=2020-03-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 29 March, the [[Dubai Metro]] and [[Dubai Tram]] were suspended until April 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubais-rta-extends-8pm-to-6am-public-transport-suspension-until-april-5-1.70694418 |title=Coronavirus: Dubai's RTA extends 8pm to 6am public transport suspension until April 5 &#124; Transport \u2013 Gulf News |publisher=Gulfnews.com |date=2020-03-29 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 31 March, [[Abu Dhabi]] installed a disinfection gate at one of its bus stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/31/abu-dhabi-sets-up-smart-disinfection-gate-at-main-bus-terminal/|title=Abu Dhabi sets up smart disinfection gate at main bus terminal\u00a0|website=The Filipino Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, [[Emirates SkyCargo]] suspended operations at the [[Al Maktoum International Airport]] and moved them to the [[Dubai International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alexander Cornwell |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/aviation/emirates-to-temporarily-shift-all-cargo-operations-to-dubai-airport |title=Emirates to temporarily shift all cargo operations to Dubai airport - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Category:COVID-19 pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n**{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/uae |title=Coronavirus UAE updates and news |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in the UAE. |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian}}\n**[https://www.doh.gov.ae/covid-19 Department of Health UAE](in English, Arabic).\n**[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/united-arab-emirates/ UAE 3736 new cases declaired](11 april update)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rentalcarsuae.com/blogs/free-sanitization-of-vehicles-offered-by-rental-cars-uae-in-dubai/|title=Free Sanitization of Vehicles offered by Rental Cars UAE in Dubai|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|United Arab Emirates|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|United Arab Emirates]]UAE\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Arab Emirates\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United Arab Emirates.svg\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in the United Arab Emirates (as of 10 February)<br />{{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}\n| map2            = \n| legend 2        = \n| map3            = \n| legend 3        = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Dubai]]<br /> [[Abu Dhabi]]<br />[[Sharjah]]\n| first_case      = [[Dubai]]\n| arrival_date    = 29 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=29|year 1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases  = 588<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d>{{cite news |last=Sebugwaawo  |first=Ismail|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-reports-376-new-coronavirus-cases170-recoveries|title=Covid-19: UAE reports 376 new coronavirus cases, 170 recoveries|accessdate=11 April 2020|work=Khaleej Times|date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 20<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| confirmed_cases = 3,736 (as of 11 April)<ref name=\u201ccases\u201d />\n| active_cases    = 3,128<ref name=\"stat.\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 CORONAVIRUS PANDEMIC |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |website=Worldometers |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n| severe_cases    = 1<ref name=\"stat.\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| fatality_rate   = 0.007%\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://covid19.ncema.gov.ae/en}}\n}}\n\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[United Arab Emirates]] was announced on 29 January 2020. It was the first country in the [[Middle East]] to report a confirmed case.<ref>Turak, Natasha (29 January 2020). [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/29/first-middle-east-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-the-uae.html First Middle East cases of coronavirus confirmed in the UAE] ''CNBC.com.'' Retrieved 19 March 2020.</ref> The first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released on 9 February after recovering. The first two deaths were confirmed on March 20. On 22 March, [[Dubai]] started an 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus. Night curfew was imposed 4 days later while the country began disinfection. School closure was first announced on April 8 for 4 weeks. 3 weeks later, it was announced that school will be closed until the end of the academic year.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases chart}}\n\n===January 2020===\nOn 23 January, [[Abu Dhabi International Airport]] and [[Dubai International Airport]] announced that travelers arriving directly from China would have their temperatures screened.<ref name=\"Khaleej23Jan2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/uae/dubai/china-coronavirus-outbreak-dubai-to-screen-passengers|title=China coronavirus outbreak: Dubai to screen passengers|last=Reuters|date=23 January 2020|website=Khaleej Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/abu-dhabi-and-dubai-airports-to-screen-passengers-for-china-coronavirus-1.968492|title=Abu Dhabi and Dubai airports to screen passengers for China coronavirus|last=Kamel|first=Deena|date=23 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January, the first case in the UAE was confirmed to be a 73-year-old Chinese woman who came to the country on holiday with her family from Wuhan.<ref name=\"first case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hammond|first=Ashley|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-how-the-first-coronavirus-case-in-uae-was-cured-1.1581323524356|title=Watch: How the first coronavirus case in UAE was cured|date=10 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Chaudhary|first2=Suchitra Bajpai|last3=Hilotin|first3=Jay}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|title=Coronavirus in UAE: Four of a family infected|last=Nandkeolyar|first=Karishma|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129111625/https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/coronavirus-in-uae-four-of-a-family-infected-1.1580273983681|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The family of four, 36-year-old mother,<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" /> 38-year-old father,<ref name=\":0\" /> 10-year-old child,<ref name=\":0\" /> and the 73-year-old grandmother arrived in the Emirates on 16 January and took the grandmother to a doctor with flu-like symptoms on 23 January, where it was discovered that the family was infected.<ref name=\"Infected family UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|title=Coronavirus: UAE records first case|last=Duncan|first=Gillian|date=29 January 2020|work=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Gautam|first2=Shuchita|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129110532/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-records-first-case-1.971253|archive-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> The announcement led to a sell out of face masks across the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|title=Coronavirus: face masks sell out across the UAE|last=Gautam|first=Shuchita|date=29 January 2020|website=The National|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129143403/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-face-masks-sell-out-across-the-uae-1.971394|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|title=Coronavirus: Most pharmacies in the UAE run out of face mask as residents rush to take protective measures|last=Ahmed|first=Ashfaq|date=29 January 2020|website=Gulf News|access-date=29 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129140304/https://gulfnews.com/uae/coronavirus-most-pharmacies-in-the-uae-run-out-of-face-mask-as-residents-rush-to-take-protective-measures-1.69347727|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the fifth case of coronavirus in the UAE was confirmed, in someone who had travelled from Wuhan to Dubai.<ref name=\"fifth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|title=UAE announces new coronavirus case|website=The National|access-date=2020-02-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201185052/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/uae-announces-new-coronavirus-case-1.972565|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-status=live}}</ref> The Dubai Health Authority (DHA) directed all DHA-licensed hospitals to consider all suspected and confirmed cases as emergencies and patients are to be treated free of charge, including those without insurance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|title=Coronavirus cases in UAE to be treated free of cost, insurance not necessary|first=Dhanusha|last=Gokulan|website=Khaleej Times|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206184719/https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-cases-in-uae-to-be-treated-free-of-cost-insurance-not-necessary--|archive-date=2020-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 8 February, the sixth and seventh cases, of Chinese and a 43-year-old [[Filipino nationality|Filipino]], were confirmed.<ref name=\"sixth and seventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/2-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-1.1581134995319|title=2 new cases of coronavirus in UAE|date=8 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=8 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/chinese-filipino-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-in-uae-bringing-total-cases-to-7-1.1581142731007|title=Chinese, Filipino diagnosed with coronavirus in UAE, bringing total cases to 7|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|date=8 February 2020|website=Gulf News |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"seventh case UAE\">{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |title=Condition of Filipino coronavirus patient in UAE 'not improving', says diplomat |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/condition-of-filipino-coronavirus-patient-in-uae-not-improving-says-diplomat-1.69834108 |accessdate=23 February 2020 |work=Gulf News |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February, the first patient, a 73-year-old Chinese woman, was released after recovering.<ref name=\"first discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Abueish|first=Tamara|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/02/09/Woman-infected-with-coronavirus-cured-UAE-.html|title=Woman infected with coronavirus cured: UAE|date=9 February 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, the eighth case was confirmed to be an Indian expatriate who had interacted with a recently diagnosed person.<ref name=\"eighth case UAE\">{{Cite news|last=Hilotin|first=Jay|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/indian-expat-in-uae-found-infected-by-coronavirus-1.1581392108339?slide=2|title=Indian expat in UAE found infected by coronavirus|date=11 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=11 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, two more patients recovered and were discharged from the hospital. The two patients were a 41-year-old Chinese father and his eight-year-old boy.<ref name=\"second discharge UAE\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/uae-announces-recovery-of-two-new-coronavirus-patients-1.1581704777547|title=UAE announces recovery of two new coronavirus patients|date=14 February 2020|work=Gulf News|access-date=16 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, the ninth case was confirmed to be a 37-year old Chinese man.<ref name=\"ninth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-ninth-case-of-coronavirus-1.1581869353798|title=UAE announces ninth case of coronavirus|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, the tenth and eleventh case were confirmed to be a 34-year-old Filipino national and a 39-year-old Bangladeshi national who had contact with a Chinese national who had been diagnosed with the virus.<ref name=\"tenth and eleventh case UAE\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKBN20F28J|title=UAE records two new coronavirus cases, total number reaches 11|date=2020-02-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the government announced that two more people, a 70-year old Iranian visitor and his 64-year-old wife, have been diagnosed, taking the total to thirteen.<ref name=\"twelfth and thirteenth case UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/iranian-couple-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-uae-taking-number-of-cases-to-13-1.69875492|title=Iranian couple diagnosed with COVID-19 in UAE, taking number of cases to 13|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, six more new cases were announced, including four Iranians, one Bahraini and one Chinese national.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/six-new-cases-of-coronavirus-reported-in-uae-1.1582821151401|title=Six new cases of coronavirus reported in UAE|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that case 2, of the 36-year-old Chinese woman, and another 37-year-old Chinese person were discharged after recovering.<ref name=\"fourteenth, fifteenth, sixteenth, seventeenth, eighteenth and nineteenth case in UAE\" />\n\nOn 28 February, two Italian technicians visiting the country to participate in the [[2020 UAE Tour|UAE Tour]], a top level cycling race, were tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-tour-cancelled-and-dozens-quarantined-as-two-participants-test-positive-1.985664|title=Coronavirus: UAE Tour cancelled and dozens quarantined as two participants test positive|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> 612 people involved in the UAE Tour were quarantined in the homes and the W Abu Dhabi hotel and the Crowne Plaza Abu Dhabi hotel, both in Yas Island, and the two hotels were put on lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aarons|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/27/chris-froome-facing-coronavirus-test-after-uae-tour-is-cancelled|title=Chris Froome facing coronavirus test after UAE Tour is cancelled|date=2020-02-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-emirates-idUSKCN20M1UW|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two Gulf hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en}}</ref> The 612 people were all screened and the results were negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/21-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-in-uae-ministry|title=21 confirmed cases of coronavirus in UAE: Ministry|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/news/2020/02/28/cyclists-await-test-results-after-coronavirus-hits-uae-tour|title=Cycle stars in lockdown as two UAE hotels isolated over coronavirus scare|website=www.gulf today.ae|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\nOn 1 March, six more people tested positive for the coronavirus in the UAE, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of infected persons to 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-six-more-cases-of-covid-19-1.987661|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces six more cases of Covid-19|website=thenational.ae}}</ref> The patients include two Russians, two Italians, a German and a Colombian citizen, who had been in contact with two Italian participants of the UAE Tour who tested positive for coronavirus at the weekend.\n\nOn 3 March, a 16-year-old female Indian student in Dubai tested positive for the coronavirus after  contracting it from her parent who came back after traveling abroad. The parent developed symptoms five days after returning to Dubai. Both the student and her family were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-dubai-school-pupil-tests-positive-for-covid-19-1.988293|title=Coronavirus: Dubai school pupil tests positive for Covid-19|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> On 5 March, the Ministry of Health and Prevention confirmed that a 17-year-old male Emirati student has tested positive for coronavirus and showed no symptoms of it. The student is now stable and is receiving necessary healthcare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-confirms-new-coronavirus-case-1.1583440148424|title=New 30th coronavirus case confirmed on student|website=Gulf News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, two Chinese patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the UAE to seven.<ref name=\"official numbers1\">{{cite news|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829181|title= UAE announces recovery of two cases of COVID-19|work=wam|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The two recoveries, a  38-year-old father and his 10-year-old child, were from the first family to contract the virus, and all members of the Chinese family are now virus-free.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/15-new-cases-of-coronavirus-in-the-uae-2-chinese-patients-recover-1.1583547467978|title=15 new cases of coronavirus in the UAE, 2 Chinese patients recover|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that 15 cases of different nationalities have tested positive for the virus, taking to 45 the total infections in the country.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> 13 cases consisted of one individual each from Thailand, China, Morocco and India, two individuals each from Saudi Arabia, Ethiopia, Iran and three individuals from the UAE were detected through early reporting by individuals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khalid|first=Tuqa|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/07/UAE-confirms-15-new-coronavirus-cases-bringing-total-up-to-44.html|title=UAE confirms 15 new coronavirus cases bringing total up to 45|date=7 March 2020|work=Al Arabiya English|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> All these cases arrived from abroad.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" /> Two cases, each from the UAE and Egypt, have been diagnosed with the virus by active surveillance system for being in close contact with confirmed cases announced previously in connection with the UAE Tour.<ref name=\"official numbers1\" />\n\nOn 9 March, the UAE recorded 14 new cases, the Ministry of Health and Prevention said, bringing the total number of reported cases to 59. In a statement, the health ministry said the cases involve four Emiratis, three Italians, two Bangladeshis, two Nepalese, a Russian, an Indian and a Syrian national.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health ministry reports 14 new coronavirus cases |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829607 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-announces-14-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1583753297673|title=14 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|access-date=9 March 2020 |work=Gulf News|date=9 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that two Emiratis, two Ethiopians and a Thai national recovered from the virus, bringing to 12 the total recovered cases in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Five more coronavirus patients recover in UAE: Health Ministry |url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302829635 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the UAE Ministry of Health and Prevention on Tuesday confirmed 15 new cases, bringing the total number of infected people in the country to 74. The 15 cases involve three Italians, two Emiratis, two from UK, two from Sri Lanka, two Indians, a German, a South African, a Tanzanian and an Iranian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-15-new-cases-announced|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 15 new cases announced|last=Wam|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that five cases recovered, consisting for three Emiratis, one Egyptian and one Moroccan.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ar:5 \u062d\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0634\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u0625\u0636\u0627\u0641\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u0635\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u062c\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 |url=https://www.wam.ae/ar/details/1395302829848 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=10 March 2020|language=ar|trans-title=Five additional recovery cases from the Coronavirus in the country}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, 11 new cases were announced, bring the total number of cases in the UAE to 85.<ref>{{cite news|last=Salman|first=Nour|url=https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830309|title=11 new COVID-19 cases in UAE: MoHAP|date=12 March 2020|work=Wam|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The individuals were placed under quarantine as suspected cases subsequent to their entry into the UAE and following required testing and monitoring, the individuals were confirmed to be positive. The 11 individuals diagnosed include two Italians, two Filipinos, one Montenegrin, one Canadian, one German, one Pakistani, one Emirati, one Russian and one British citizen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-uae-confirms-11-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 11 new cases of Covid-19|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On the same day, it was announced that a Bangladeshi, a Chinese, and an Italian person recovered from the virus, bringing the total number of recovered cases in the country to 20.<ref name=\"recoveries2\">{{cite news |last=Alfaham |first= Tariq |title= Three more people recover from coronavirus in UAE |url= https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395302830394 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Wam |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, 12 new cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 98. The patients are three Indians, and one each from the UAE, the Philippines, South Africa, Australia, China, Lebanon, the UK, Italy, and Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-confirms-12-new-cases-1.992864|title=12 new cases of COVID-19 in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> \nOn the same day, 3 people have recovered from the virus bringing the total number to 26, the people are two Emiratis and an Indian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-three-more-recover-in-the-uae-1.992496|title= 3 new COVID-19 recoveries in the UAE|website= The National}}</ref> On 18 March, 15 new cases were announced, with the total number of infected people to 113. Patients are from Kyrgyzstan, Serbia, Italy, Netherlands, Australia, Germany, USA, Greece, Russia, Ukraine, Bangladesh, Britain, and Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/health/coronavirus-uae-announces-15-new-cases-of-covid-19-1.994024|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 15 new cases of Covid-19|website=The National}}</ref> On 19 March, UAE confirmed 27 new cases of the novel coronavirus on Thursday along with 30 recoveries in total.\nThe total number of COVID-19 cases in UAE stands at 140, Ministry of Health and Prevention said today in a press conference. Dr. Farida Al Hosani, Director of Communicable Diseases Department at the Health Department said the total number of cases have reached 140. She said five more cases have recovered including three Emiratis, one Syrian and one Sri Lankan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-27-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 27 new cases confirmed|last=Sebugwawo|first=Ismail|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 20 March, the first two deaths were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-emirates-tally/uae-announces-first-two-deaths-from-coronavirus-wam-idUSKBN2173JU|title=UAE Announces First Two Deaths From Coronavirus: WAM|website=Reuters|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, The Ministry of Health and Prevention made the announcement. One of the two cases is 78-year old Arab national who came from Europe and tested positive for COVID-19 and died due to heart attack while the other is a 59-year-old Asian expat who was suffering from chronic diseases including heart disease and kidney failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/uae-announces-2-coronavirus-deaths-1.1584735850926|title=UAE announces 2 coronavirus deaths|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, there were seven recovery cases, but however, there were 13 new cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-13-new-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-1|title=Covid-19 in UAE: 13 new cases, seven recoveries confirmed|first=Web|last=Report|website=Khaleej Times}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] announced that it will be suspending all passenger flights effective March 25 in response to the coronavirus, but will continue to operate cargo flights for essential goods.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://apnews.com/10aa229f979a05241ede3c349f5e4d2d | title=Dubai's Emirates cuts passenger flights to 13 destinations| date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[UAE]] announces 45 new coronavirus cases. Total cases reported in the country are now 198.<ref name=\"gulfnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-45-new-coronavirus-cases-1.1584969735068|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 45 new coronavirus cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government urged people to stay in their homes and only leave home for an emergency or for work, said Ministry of Interior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-urges-people-to-stay-in-their-homes-1.1584916668613|title=Coronavirus: UAE urges people to stay in their homes|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government shut malls for two weeks. Fish, meat and vegetable markets also closed for a renewable period of two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-shuts-malls-for-two-weeks-1.1584914600541|title=Coronavirus: UAE shuts malls for two weeks|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> The government also suspended all passenger and transit flights. The suspension of flights will commence at 23:59 (UAE local time) on Wednesday 25 March and will last for an initial 14 days, subject to further directives by the relevant authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/aviation/coronavirus-uae-suspends-all-passenger-and-transit-flights-1.1584917287850|title=Coronavirus: UAE suspends all passenger and transit flights|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Telecommunications Regulatory Authority (UAE)|TRA]] unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid the coronavirus outbreak. The TRA explained that residents will now be able to use Microsoft Teams, Zoom and Blackboard, which are available on all networks in the country. Microsoft Skype for Business and Google Hangouts are compatible with fixed Internet networks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-tra-unblocks-skype-for-business-google-hangouts-amid-covid-19-outbreak-1.1585047632245|title=UAE: TRA unblocks Skype for Business, Google Hangouts amid COVID-19 outbreak|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> Four new recovery cases and 50 new cases were confirmed. These new cases were among individuals who had close contact with cases announced previously, as well as people who returned from abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-in-uae-50-new-cases-confirmed|title=Coronavirus in UAE: 50 new cases confirmed|website= www.khaleejtimes.com/}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, UAE announces 85 new cases, the total number of infections in the country reaches 333, with seven recoveries reported on Wednesday, March 25. The announcement was made during a regular media briefing held Wednesday, March 25 by Farida Al Hosani, official spokesperson of the UAE health sector. Seven people were recovered making the total recoveries in the UAE 52.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-announces-85-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585141534235|title=Coronavirus: UAE announces 85 new COVID-19 cases|website= gulfnews.com}}</ref> On the same day, 64 people were arrested for breaking home quarantine after they came in direct contact with people infected with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/crime/coronavirus-uae-arrests-64-for-breaking-home-quarantine-law-1.1585155529277|title=Coronavirus: UAE arrests 64 for breaking home quarantine law|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, UAE 72 new cases and three recoveries were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/coronavirus-uae-reports-72-new-covid-19-cases-1.1585331041900|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 72 new corona virus cases|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, UAE on Saturday announced 63 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total of confirmed cases to 468.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-63-new-cases-of-covid-19-on-saturday-1.1585401355346 |title = Coronavirus: UAE: 63 new cases of COVID-19 on Saturday}}</ref> On 29 March, UAE the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 102 new cases, taking the total cases in the country to 570. The 102 new cases patients consisted of one person from New Zealand, Slovakia, Morocco, Greece, China, France, Germany, Algeria, Iraq, Colombia, Venezuela, and Poland. Two people from Brazil, Sweden, Australia, Ethiopia, Canada, Lebanon, Sudan, Saudi Arabia, and Portugal. Three people from Italy and Ireland. Six people from Egypt. Seven people from the UAE and the Philippines. 16 people from Britain. 30 people from India. On the same day, the three new recoveries were announced takes the total tally of recoveries to 58, and another person died from the virus, taking the toll to three in UAE, until March 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-outbreak/covid-19-in-uae-102-new-cases-announced-3-recoveries|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 102 new corona virus cases|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, UAE announced 41 new cases of COVID-19, raising the total number of confirmed cases in the country to 611. All are in stable condition except two, who are in critical condition. Two more deaths have been announced as well. The total death toll is now five. Three recoveries have also been announced - two Indians and one Filipino.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-41-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1585573506275|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 41 new corona virus cases|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 31 March, UAE The Ministry of Health and Prevention in the UAE has announced 53 new confirmed cases of the coronavirus and one death. The total cases reported in the country is now 664. One death has also been announced, taking the total toll to six. The new cases include one each from Algeria, Lebanon, Pakistan, Iran, Kuwait, Switzerland, Turkey, the Philippines, Italy, France, America and two people from Egypt, Nepal, three people from Britain, four people from the UAE, and as many as 31 people from India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-reports-53-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1585660904284|title=COVID-19: UAE announces 53 new corona virus cases|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Moreover, Al Ras area, one of the city's densely populated areas that's home to the gold souk and museums, was placed under lock down for two weeks starting 31 March preventing all residents from leaving or entering the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-31/dubai-locks-down-historic-neighborhood-to-prevent-virus-spread|title=Dubai Locks Down Historic Neighborhood to Prevent Virus Spread|last=Elbahrawy|first=Farah|date=31 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nOn 1 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 150 new coronavirus cases for a total of 814, with a total number of eight deaths from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-150-new-cases-1|title=COVID-19: UAE confirms 150 new cases, two deaths|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention announced 210 new cases for a total number of cases to 1,024, with 96 recoveries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wam.ae/en/details/1395302834594|title=COVID-19: Ministry of Health announces 210 new cases of COVID-19, 35 recoveries among various nationalities|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, 240 new cases were announced for a total of 1,264, with 108 having fully recovered, and one patient having died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-confirms-240-new-cases-on-friday |title= Covid-19: One expat dead, 240 new cases in UAE |website= Khaleej Times \\accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported another 241 new coronavirus cases, bringing the total number of COVID-19 patients to 1,505.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/covid-19-241-new-coronavirus-cases-reported-in-uae-on-saturday-1.1586001691620 |title=COVID-19: 1 death, 241 new coronavirus cases reported in UAE on Saturday  |website=gulfnews.com |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported 294 new cases of the COVID-19 coronavirus, taking the total number of cases in the country to 1,799. MoHAP also announced 19 new recoveries, taking the total number of recoveries to 144.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-294-new-cases-of-covid-19 |title= Coronavirus: UAE confirms 294 new cases, 19 recoveries |website=Khaleej Times |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, the Ministry of Health and Prevention reported another 277 new coronavirus cases of different nationalities, bringing the total number of cases of infection to 2076, with 11 deaths from the virus, and a total of 167 recovered patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-277-new-coronavirus-cases-one-death-1.1586170041645 |title=COVID-19: UAE announces 277 new coronavirus cases, one death |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, The Ministry of Health and Community Protection announced it was monitoring 283 new cases of coronavirus, bringing the number of diagnosed cases to 2359. The Ministry also announced the total of the cases of recovery to 186, with a total number of 12 deaths due to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/coronavirus-uae-confirms-283-new-cases-april-7-1- | title=Coronavirus: UAE confirms 283 new cases of COVID-19 |website=Khaleej Times |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, 300 new cases and 53 new recoveries were announced, with the total number of cases standing at 2,659, with 239 recoveries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-announces-300-new-cases-of-coronavirus |title=Covid-19: UAE announces 300 new cases of coronavirus - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, there were 331 new coronavirus cases and two deaths, with a total of 14 deaths.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/Covid-19-in-UAE-331-new-cases-29-recoveries-announced|title=Covid-19: The UAE reported 331 new coronavirus cases - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, there were 370 new confirmed cases, for a total of 3,360. 150 patients recovered, bringing the total number of recovered cases to 418. There were two deaths from the virus, for a total of 16.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/covid-19-uae-announces-370-new-coronavirus-cases-two-deaths-1.1586541879415|title=Covid-19: UAE announces 370 new coronavirus cases, two deaths - News |publisher=Gulf News|date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, there were 376 new cases of coronavirus, for a total of 3,736. The total number of recoveries rose to 588. Four patients died of the virus, bringing the total number of deaths to 20.<ref>{{cite web|author=Web Report |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/coronavirus-pandemic/covid-19-uae-reports-376-new-coronavirus-cases170-recoveries|title=Covid-19: UAE reports 376 new coronavirus cases, 170 recoveries - News |publisher=Khaleej Times|date= |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nOn 22 March, [[Dubai]] started a 11-day sterilisation campaign as an effort to contain the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tesorero |first1=Angel |last2=Nasrallah |first2=Tawfiq |title=Watch: Dubai starts massive coronavirus sterilisation drive |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/health/watch-dubai-starts-massive-coronavirus-sterilisation-drive-1.70524415 |access-date=2020-03-20 |work=Gulf News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, the country imposed night curfew as disinfection in the country began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/coronavirus-uae-imposes-overnight-curfew-disinfection-campaign|title=Coronavirus: UAE imposes night curfew as it carries out disinfection campaign|website=Middle East Eye|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, Dubai lifted their ban on trucks weighting 2.5 tonnes.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://gulfnews.com/amp/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubai-temporarily-lifts-ban-on-movement-of-trucks-1.70618893 |title=Coronavirus: Dubai temporarily lifts ban on movement of trucks |publisher=Gulfnews.com |date=2020-03-25 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 28 March, the country announced that curfews and disinfection would be extended until April 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/443885-uae-extends-sterilisation-programme-until-april-5|title=UAE extends nationwide coronavirus disinfection programme, curfews until April 5|website=ArabianBusiness.com|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Abu Dhabi]] crown prince [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan|Mohammed bin Zayed]] announced that a new testing site has opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/gulf/2020/03/28/UAE-launches-mobile-drive-through-coronavirus-test-center |title=UAE launches mobile drive-through coronavirus test center |publisher=Al Arabiya English |date=2020-03-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 29 March, the [[Dubai Metro]] and [[Dubai Tram]] were suspended until April 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/transport/coronavirus-dubais-rta-extends-8pm-to-6am-public-transport-suspension-until-april-5-1.70694418 |title=Coronavirus: Dubai's RTA extends 8pm to 6am public transport suspension until April 5 &#124; Transport \u2013 Gulf News |publisher=Gulfnews.com |date=2020-03-29 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> On 31 March, [[Abu Dhabi]] installed a disinfection gate at one of its bus stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filipinotimes.net/news/2020/03/31/abu-dhabi-sets-up-smart-disinfection-gate-at-main-bus-terminal/|title=Abu Dhabi sets up smart disinfection gate at main bus terminal\u00a0|website=The Filipino Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April, [[Emirates SkyCargo]] suspended operations at the [[Al Maktoum International Airport]] and moved them to the [[Dubai International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alexander Cornwell |url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/aviation/emirates-to-temporarily-shift-all-cargo-operations-to-dubai-airport |title=Emirates to temporarily shift all cargo operations to Dubai airport - News |publisher=Khaleej Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United Arab Emirates medical cases}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Category:COVID-19 pandemic in the United Arab Emirates}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n**{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/uae |title=Coronavirus UAE updates and news |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in the UAE. |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian}}\n**[https://www.doh.gov.ae/covid-19 Department of Health UAE](in English, Arabic).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|United Arab Emirates|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|United Arab Emirates]]UAE\n", "name_user": "Ahsaan. Itmaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "New 11 april update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_Arab_Emirates"}
{"title_page": "The Doon School", "text_new": "{{Under construction}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Independent [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 houses + 2 holding houses\n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]], [[Selective school|selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires. Although he died in 1928, he is considered the founder of the school. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], an Englishman who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster was [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020. He was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].\n\nThe school houses roughly 500 pupils aged 12 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination, a group discussion and an interview with the headmaster. Every year in January and April, the school admits pupils aged 13 in Grade 7 (known as D-form) and aged 14 in Grade 8 (C-form) respectively. Boys take the [[IGCSE]] exam in Grade 10, and for the final two years can choose between [[Indian School Certificate]] or [[International Baccalaureate]] curriculum. Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders, including former [[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]], to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]]. [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are known as 'Doscos'. \n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/17-schools-from-u---khand-secure-top-10-positions-in-ewisr.html|title=17 schools from U\u2019khand secure Top 10 positions in EWISR|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=\"Spectator UK\">{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/03/its-a-spartan-life-at-the-eton-of-india/# |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> and ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> it strongly eschews the label.<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including politicians, diplomats, artists, writers and business leaders.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Among the former pupils of Doon are the late Indian prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], artist [[Anish Kapoor]], novelists [[Vikram Seth]] and [[Amitav Ghosh]], fashion designer [[Tarun Tahiliani]], mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] and social activist [[Bunker Roy]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006-page100</ref><ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises. With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status. Under the IPSS, a Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Das in 1928, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money. To solve this problem, Sir Joseph Bhore, then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] in [[Dehra Dun]] on favourable terms. Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> On 27 October 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref>\n\nThe [[House system|houses]] at the new school were originally named after their respective [[housemaster]]s, but later renamed in honour of the largest donor to the IPSS: Hyderabad House was named after Sir [[Akbar Hydari]] secured a contribution of {{Indian Rupee}}200,000 from the [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government; [[Kashmir House]], after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]], promised a contribution of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000, which was delivered in 1935; Tata House, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] and [[Wadia family|Wadia]] Trusts promised {{Indian Rupee}}150,000, half of which was delivered in 1935; Jaipur House, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000 from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> No building was named after [[Rai Bahadur]] Rameshwar Nathany, since his donation of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000 was initially anonymous.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/constructingpost0000sriv |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/constructingpost0000sriv/page/224 224] |quote=rai bahadur. |title=Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School|publisher=Psychology Press |first=Sanjay|last=Srivastava |accessdate=6 March 2012|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\n[[Arthur Foot]] had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become Principal of [[Mayo College]]. They were soon joined in their efforts by equally influential Indians such as [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a pioneering mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" />&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nIn an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> Martyn, who became the second headmaster, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Martyn acknowledged Foot's leadership in the school's development, but added that they both had similar ideas: \"I would not have been as bold as he was in trying to eliminate punishments, but we were equally keen on providing as wide a range as possible of activities that were creative and challenging&nbsp;... The problem, as we saw it, was to create an atmosphere in which boys would learn the importance of public spirit at the same time as they acquired self-confidence and initiative.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref>\n\nWhile the first two headmasters, Foot and Martyn, were determined to model Doon on Eton and Harrow, they both agreed that Doon should cater primarily for Indian boys and not the sons of British expatriates, in order to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution. The early headmasters and teachers came from traditional British public schools and the jargon introduced by them is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Though Foot was inspired by elite British institutions, he did not want Doon to be considered elitist. Foot once said, \"our boys will join an aristocracy, but it\u2019s an aristocracy of service inspired by ideals of unselfishness, not one of wealth, privilege or position\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Middle years: 1970\u20132000===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/05/16/stories/2007051615082000.htm |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> During Simeon's tenure of nine years, the school faced financial difficulties and the estate suffered as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities. <ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1971, Simeon introduced the 'Scholar's Blazer', an academic equivalent of the pre-existing prize 'Games Blazer', so that boys accorded academic achievement the same level of prestige as they did success in sports.<ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster. In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was on upgrading the school infrastructure, and during his tenure the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils, therefore the school did not raise its fees during his tenure. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration. His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon cabinet\" or \"Dosco Mafia\"<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Naveen Patnaik, and Rahul Gandhi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Recent years: 2000\u2013present===\n[[Kanti Bajpai]] was the third old boy, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das, to become headmaste, when appointed to the post in 2003. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The fact came to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Despite mounting pressure, the school's board of governors appealed for maintaining the status quo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''[[jhatka]]'') meat varieties in the dining hall.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades.\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations and film controversy====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the school's 75th Founder's Day in October 2010.]]\n\nFounder's Day is a three-four day event in the autumn term, usually October, that marks the school's founding and draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> The chief guest is usually a prominent person.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The events include exhibitions, productions of plays, yoga sessions, live bands, a fete and an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Hill Post|url=http://hillpost.in/2011/10/28/doon-school-celebrates-76-th-founders-day/33352/latest-news/bhatt |title=Doon School celebrates 76 th founders day |date=28 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day in 2010 and programmed events on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/doon-school-to-celebrate-its-75th-anniversary-from-oct-21/articleshow/6712783.cms?from=mdr|title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21|date=8 October 2010|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/boys-will-be-boys/story-UxdKhDLhEGUVHIwaXe2e7H.html|title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The event was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President [[Pratibha Patil]] of India, King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan and [[Kapil Sibal]], (then [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Union Minister for Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101025/jsp/frontpage/story_13097199.jsp |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]], an alumnus and Oscar-nominated director, made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> It was screened on the final day of celebrations to a gathering of over 2000 people, including guests, students, parents and alumni.<ref name=dazed>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-interviews/28271042_1_film-doon-school-ashvin-kumar|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film|newspaper=The Times of India|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The day after screening, the school objected to the film and its distribution, obtaining a court order to delay its release and labelling it \"defamatory\".<ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-18/news-interviews/28230561_1_doon-short-film-ashvin|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The DVD sales on campus were immediately halted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-School-bans-Ashvin-Kumars-film/articleshow/6919672.cms|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=ex-student-film>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701125916/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 July 2012|title=Ex-student's film celebrating Doon draws school's ire|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 December 2010}}</ref> The dispute  remains unresolved between the director and school authorities. On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Present day====\nIn June 2016, the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin as headmaster. Until the start of McLaughlin's headmastership, the student demographic was dominated by boys hailing from the [[North Indian]] states. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's outreach initiative of inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian|South]] and [[Northeast India|Northeast Indian]] states.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school occupies a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. \n\n===Architecture===\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received an \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe Chandbagh estate is located adjacent to [[Dehradun Cantonment]] in the green zone of [[Dehradun]], and a wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on the estate, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the Forest Research Institute.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/doon-schools-etp-may-be-trendsetter/428364/ |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus, known as Chandbagh.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), where new students live for a year before moving to one of the main houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Boys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses.\n\nEach housemaster and housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support.\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main Building of the school which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-07-04/special-report/27149351_1_education-system-elite-schools-vikram-seth |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: Spring, Summer and Autumn. New pupils (\"D-Formers or 7th Graders\") join Doon at the beginning of April.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> The Autumn Term runs from August to the year-end examinations in November after which the boys are promoted to the new class beginning in February. These internal examinations are known as \"trials\", while examinations leading to certificates such as the [[Indian School Certificate]] are known as \"finals\". Discipline at the school has always been strict, and the school has expelled children from well-known families. In the 1950s, Martyn's suggestion that [[Sanjay Gandhi]] finish his senior year elsewhere was accepted without question by his mother, Indira Gandhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20081202/dplus1.htm |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2014 Dehradun Plus |work=The Tribune |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> \n\nSocial work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]] the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>  \n\n===School songs===\nThe school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School Prayer book p.02-26</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's Song Book, which includes: ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]]; ''[[Saare Jahan Se Achcha]]'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal; ''Vandana Ke in Swaron Mein'' (a [[Bhajan|bhajan]]); ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]); ''Pitu Matu Sahayak'' (a bhajan); ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the School Song in 1935, fifteen years before it was adopted as India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at Doon.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory for pupils. The school has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket and hockey dominate the sports calendar in spring term, while football, athletics and boxing are played in autumn term. Other sports such as tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics are played all-year round. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium, yoga studio, and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks. In 2014, the school inaugurated a shooting range on campus. Golf is offered to boys in partnership with local golf courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref> Doon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school tournament that draws all major school basketball teams of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/features/the-asian-school-bag-bball-trophy-233461 |title=The Asian School bag b\u2019ball trophy |publisher=The Tribune India |date=2016-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys visit other schools and academies from time to time to take part in various tournaments. For skill improvement, the school often invites professional sports bodies to hold training camps, which are usually open to students from across India. In 2013, a football coaching camp was held in association with Bar\u00e7a Academy, the official training school of [[FC Barcelona]],<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/f-c-barcelona-at-doon-july-2013/</ref> and in January 2015, coaches from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] held a week-long cricket training camp on the school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchvision.com/exclusive-inside-mcc-lords-club-india-coaching-camp-drills |title=Live Local Matches &#124; Tips & Techniques &#124; Articles & Podcasts |publisher=PitchVision |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=September_2015&Section=Boarding_Schools&Article=India%27s_best_boys_boarding_school</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon. It is produced by the boys and distributed every Saturday morning.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life.  There are around 70-80 clubs and societies, including astronomy, business, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], quiz, photography and film, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], robotics, paper recycling, weather reporting, pottery, carpentry, [[amateur radio]] and birdwatching, among others.<ref>{{cite web|author=\" + arr[2] + \" |url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412 |title=Premium schools |publisher=Outlook Business |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nBoys can write for, or join the editorial board of, a number of school magazines that are published in English or Hindi. ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication and the official school newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/34/42/obituary/ |title=OBITUARY : Himalayan Journal vol.34/42 |publisher=Himalayanclub.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Distributed every Saturday morning, and edited by pupils, it chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative, political or humorous writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the school community as well as Old Boys, and include satire and criticism of school policies. More subversive publications, critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other magazines include ''The Yearbook'', a heavily illustrated publication for recording all highlights of the school year, and ''The Doon School Information Review'' for cultural criticism. Specialist publications by academic departments include '' Vibgyor'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys take a one-week \"midterm\"&nbsp;\u2013 a rugged trip, often through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents, cooking their own food and hiking. They plan these trips themselves. Alumni have credited these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nDoon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] and alumni such as [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nSome of these expeditions have had their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth has been claimed to hold the high-altitude record for smoking a pipe, which he did on the summit of [[Kamet]] after the first ascent in 1931.<ref name=\"Harish Kapadia\"> {{cite book |last1=Kapadia |first1=Harish |title=Across Peaks and Passes in Garhwal Himalaya |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Across_Peaks_Passes_in_Garhwal_Himalaya.html?id=KptmxrqhKl4C |date=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |location=London |language=English |isbn=9788173870972 |page=17 |quote=The peak of Kamet was attempted several times and finally in 1931 Frank Smythe and Eric Shipton reached the summit along with some others. R.L. Holdsworth, who was with them, smoked a pipe on the summit, which I believe still remains a height record for smokers.}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001 a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002 the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}} 2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/04/11/stories/2002041100070300.htm |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/lf/2002/03/30/stories/2002033000930200.htm |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its Platinum Jubilee, the school launched a music album called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-and-interviews/28261521_1_music-album-doscos-alumni |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The school choir sang two songs (\"Lab pe Aati Hai Dua\" and \"Anand Loke\") for the project but only the former was included in the final recording. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\" />\n\n==Affiliations==\n\n===Ties with other schools===\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became Principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Several families who send their sons to Doon send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> Doon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-24/special-report/28263544_1_doon-school-ipsc-sainik-schools |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Memberships===\nThe Doon School is a member of following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Interact Club|Rotary International's Interact Club]], [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=38&filter_data7=&filter_data10=INDIA&filter_data13=&filter_data15=&key=&submit=SEARCH |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examinations]], [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO)]], Indian Public Schools' Conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802223143/http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |title=Indian Public Schools' Conference |publisher=Ipsc.co.in |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)]], [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the School on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\". The dispute remains unresolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-path-not-taken/article2924231.ece|title=The path not taken|first=Sudhish|last=Kamath|date=23 February 2012|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The documentary was produced in association with the [[British Council]]. Its main purpose was to show the school where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the all-round experience of an Indian residential school. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Huang |first1=Guiyou |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Asian American Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Greenwood_Encyclopedia_of_Asian_Amer.html?id=d5RxDwAAQBAJ |date=2009 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |language= |isbn=9781567207361 |page=860 |quote=...as a boarder at the prestigious Doon School, known as \"the Eton of India\" on Dehradun. Whilst at school, Seth encountered abuse and bullying from many of his fellow classmates, an experience that he later evokes by the character Tapan, the youngest of the Chaterjees, in ''A Suitable Boy''.}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Damrosch |first1=David |title=How to Read World Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/How_to_Read_World_Literature.html?id=1VYsDwAAQBAJ |date=2017 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Son]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781119009245 |page=172 |quote=Chekhov and Zulu became ''Star Trek'' devotees while still in school in India...Significantly, they are enrolled in the Doon School, an elite British-style academy established in the waning years of British Raj.}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" due to the fact that the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bond |first1=Ruskin |title=Strangers in the Night |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Strangers_on_the_Roof.html?id=58nqMgEACAAJ |date=1994 |publisher=[[Penguin Books India]] |location= |language= |isbn=9780140240658 |page=4 |quote=William and Jai did not trail me to this place, as it was a little lowbrow for them (William being Swiss and Jai being Doon School.}}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://raifilm.org.uk/films/doon-school-chronicles/|title=Film : \u201cDoon School Chronicles\u201d \u2013 RAI Ethnographic Film Catalogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School alumni}}\n[[File:Rahul Gandhi at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Rahul Gandhi]] (Class of 1988), Indian politician, [[Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]] speaking at The Doon School Model United Nations' Conference in August 2017.]]\n\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Pupils of Doon have gone on to achieve prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\" /><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> They include nine [[Union Cabinet of India|Cabinet Ministers]], two [[chief minister]]s, several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]]; nineteen generals, two admirals, former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces and twenty-four ambassadors, including those from India, Pakistan, Nepal and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/06/01/stories/2009060153270700.htm |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was educated at Doon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/magazine/mrs-gandhi-grooms-another-son.html|title=Mrs. Gandhi Grooms Another Son|first=Michael T.|last=Kaufman|date=13 June 1982|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|thumb|left|160px|[[Bunker Roy]], Social activist and the founder of [[Barefoot College]], [[Tilonia]].]]\nNotable Doon alumni to have held senior positions in Indian and Pakistani politics include the former Indian diplomat turned politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], currently a Rajya Sabha nominee, the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], politician [[Kamal Nath]], [[Rahul Gandhi]], [[Sanjay Gandhi]], [[Chief Minister of Odisha ]]  politician [[Naveen Patnaik]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]], politican and poet [[Karan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930/ |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> In the field of literature and poetry, Doon alumni include novelists [[Amitav Ghosh]], [[Vikram Seth]], historian [[Ramachandra Guha]], and [[Ardashir Vakil]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/microsoft-s-new-boss-is-a-window-on-a-better-school-system-9115621.html|title=Microsoft\u2019s new boss is a window on a better school system|date=7 February 2014|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon alumni in journalism include [[Prannoy Roy]], [[Aroon Purie]], [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chandra |first=Ram |url=http://www.careers360.com/news/3632-Aroon-Purie-Editor-in-Chief-India-Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124094457/http://www.careers360.com/news/3632-Aroon-Purie-Editor-in-Chief-India-Today |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 November 2009 |title=Aroon Purie on Education |journal=Careers 360 News Magazine |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012 }}</ref> The first Indian [[Rhodes scholar]] was a Doon School alumni - [[Lovraj Kumar]].<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon is also the alma mater of the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, [[Abhinav Bindra]] and the mountaineering pioneer [[Nandu Jayal]].<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Anish Kapoor at the Deutsche Guggenheim - Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|160px|[[Anish Kapoor]] is a sculptor whose designs include [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]].<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/>]] In the field of arts and entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Ali Fazal]], [[Roshan Seth]], [[Himani Shivpuri]], [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]] and [[Abhishek Poddar]], a prominent art collector.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/article2890613.ece |title=A Renaissance Woman|newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Turner Prize]]-winning sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> In business, the Doon alumni include [[Analjit Singh]] of Max Group, [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], chairman of [[Hero MotoCorp]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref>  [[Anil Kumar]], former senior partner at [[McKinsey & Company]] and co-founder of the [[Indian School of Business]], [[Gautam Thapar]], founder and chairman of the [[Avantha Group]], [[Malvinder Mohan Singh]] and [[Shivinder Mohan Singh]], former owners of [[Fortis Healthcare]], [[Ajay S. Shriram]], managing director of [[DCM Shriram group]] and [[Sharan Pasricha]], CEO of Ennismore hospitality developer and founder of [[The Hoxton]] and [[Gleneagles Hotel|Gleneagles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/gleneagles-is-a-sleeping-giant-well-make-it-the-best-hotel-in-the-world-lbhjf75z0|title=\u2018Gleneagles is a sleeping giant. We\u2019ll make it the best hotel in the world\u2019|first=Dominic|last=Walsh|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/IN/XNSE/DCMSHRIRAM/company-people/executive-profile/10062|title=DCMSHRIRAM.IN Company Profile & Executives - DCM Shriram Ltd. - Wall Street Journal|website=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nIn the early years, many teachers came from British schools, including [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]] from Eton College,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] from [[Ripon Grammar School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]] and [[R. L. Holdsworth]] from Harrow.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The school's first art teacher was the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]], from [[Visva-Bharati University|Shantiniketan]], who joined in 1936 and remained at school for twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Many sculptures and murals on the campus today were created by him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jnaf.org/artist/sudhir-khastgir/|title=Sudhir Khastgir - JNAF}}</ref> The film director [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]] taught briefly at the school from 1940 to 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/dev-anand-chetan-anand-doon-school-dehradun/story/1/19703.html|title=How Doon School inspired the inimitable Dev Anand style|website=www.dailyo.in}}</ref> Mountaineer [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] joined in 1946 as a geography teacher and led the boys on many expeditions.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/50-years-later-its-happily-Everest-after/articleshow/46893756.cms|title=50 years later, it's happily Everest after &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The cricketer and mathematics teacher, [[Sheel Vohra]], joined in 1959 and became the longest-serving master in school's history when he retired in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/remembering-sheel-vohra-doon-schools-beloved-bond.html|title=Remembering Sheel Vohra, Doon School's beloved 'Bond'|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> The [[Fiji-Indian]] academic [[Satendra Nandan]] taught history at school in the early 1960s, and the [[sarod]] player [[Ashok Roy]] headed the music department from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Popular science]] author and theoretical physicist, [[Simon Singh]], taught science at Doon in 1987 before embarking on his academic and writing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010 {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], IPSS (1985) edited by Sumer Singh, published by the Indian Public Schools Society 1985. ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''],  a periodic newsletter by the Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, published by [[Routledge]] 1998 {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Under construction}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Independent [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 houses + 2 holding houses\n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]], [[Selective school|selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires. Although he died in 1928, he is considered the founder of the school. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], an Englishman who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster was [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020. He was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].\n\nDoon houses roughly 500 pupils aged 13 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination, a group discussion and an interview with the headmaster. Every year in January and April, the school admits pupils aged 13 in Grade 7 (known as D-form) and aged 14 in Grade 8 (C-form) respectively. Boys take the [[IGCSE]] exam in Grade 10, and for the final two years can choose between [[Indian School Certificate]] or [[International Baccalaureate]] curriculum. Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders, including former [[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]], to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]]. [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are known as 'Doscos'. \n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/17-schools-from-u---khand-secure-top-10-positions-in-ewisr.html|title=17 schools from U\u2019khand secure Top 10 positions in EWISR|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=\"Spectator UK\">{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/03/its-a-spartan-life-at-the-eton-of-india/# |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> and ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> it strongly eschews the label.<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including politicians, diplomats, artists, writers and business leaders.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Among the former pupils of Doon are the late Indian prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], artist [[Anish Kapoor]], novelists [[Vikram Seth]] and [[Amitav Ghosh]], fashion designer [[Tarun Tahiliani]], mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] and social activist [[Bunker Roy]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006-page100</ref><ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises. With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status. Under the IPSS, a Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Das in 1928, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money. To solve this problem, Sir Joseph Bhore, then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] in [[Dehra Dun]] on favourable terms. Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> On 27 October 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref>\n\nThe [[House system|houses]] at the new school were originally named after their respective [[housemaster]]s, but later renamed in honour of the largest donor to the IPSS: Hyderabad House was named after Sir [[Akbar Hydari]] secured a contribution of {{Indian Rupee}}200,000 from the [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government; [[Kashmir House]], after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]], promised a contribution of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000, which was delivered in 1935; Tata House, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] and [[Wadia family|Wadia]] Trusts promised {{Indian Rupee}}150,000, half of which was delivered in 1935; Jaipur House, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000 from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> No building was named after [[Rai Bahadur]] Rameshwar Nathany, since his donation of {{Indian Rupee}}100,000 was initially anonymous.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/constructingpost0000sriv |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/constructingpost0000sriv/page/224 224] |quote=rai bahadur. |title=Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School|publisher=Psychology Press |first=Sanjay|last=Srivastava |accessdate=6 March 2012|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\n[[Arthur Foot]] had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become Principal of [[Mayo College]]. They were soon joined in their efforts by equally influential Indians such as [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a pioneering mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" />&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nIn an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> Martyn, who became the second headmaster, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Martyn acknowledged Foot's leadership in the school's development, but added that they both had similar ideas: \"I would not have been as bold as he was in trying to eliminate punishments, but we were equally keen on providing as wide a range as possible of activities that were creative and challenging&nbsp;... The problem, as we saw it, was to create an atmosphere in which boys would learn the importance of public spirit at the same time as they acquired self-confidence and initiative.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref>\n\nWhile the first two headmasters, Foot and Martyn, were determined to model Doon on Eton and Harrow, they both agreed that Doon should cater primarily for Indian boys and not the sons of British expatriates, in order to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution. The early headmasters and teachers came from traditional British public schools and the jargon introduced by them is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Though Foot was inspired by elite British institutions, he did not want Doon to be considered elitist. Foot once said, \"our boys will join an aristocracy, but it\u2019s an aristocracy of service inspired by ideals of unselfishness, not one of wealth, privilege or position\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Middle years: 1970\u20132000===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/05/16/stories/2007051615082000.htm |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> During Simeon's tenure of nine years, the school faced financial difficulties and the estate suffered as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities. <ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1971, Simeon introduced the 'Scholar's Blazer', an academic equivalent of the pre-existing prize 'Games Blazer', so that boys accorded academic achievement the same level of prestige as they did success in sports.<ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster. In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was on upgrading the school infrastructure, and during his tenure the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils, therefore the school did not raise its fees during his tenure. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration. His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon cabinet\" or \"Dosco Mafia\"<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Naveen Patnaik, and Rahul Gandhi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Recent years: 2000\u2013present===\n[[Kanti Bajpai]] was the third old boy, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das, to become headmaste, when appointed to the post in 2003. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The fact came to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Despite mounting pressure, the school's board of governors appealed for maintaining the status quo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''[[jhatka]]'') meat varieties in the dining hall.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades.\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations and film controversy====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the school's 75th Founder's Day in October 2010.]]\n\nFounder's Day is a three-four day event in the autumn term, usually October, that marks the school's founding and draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> The chief guest is usually a prominent person.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The events include exhibitions, productions of plays, yoga sessions, live bands, a fete and an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Hill Post|url=http://hillpost.in/2011/10/28/doon-school-celebrates-76-th-founders-day/33352/latest-news/bhatt |title=Doon School celebrates 76 th founders day |date=28 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day in 2010 and programmed events on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/doon-school-to-celebrate-its-75th-anniversary-from-oct-21/articleshow/6712783.cms?from=mdr|title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21|date=8 October 2010|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/boys-will-be-boys/story-UxdKhDLhEGUVHIwaXe2e7H.html|title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The event was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President [[Pratibha Patil]] of India, King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan and [[Kapil Sibal]], (then [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Union Minister for Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101025/jsp/frontpage/story_13097199.jsp |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]], an alumnus and Oscar-nominated director, made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> It was screened on the final day of celebrations to a gathering of over 2000 people, including guests, students, parents and alumni.<ref name=dazed>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-interviews/28271042_1_film-doon-school-ashvin-kumar|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film|newspaper=The Times of India|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The day after screening, the school objected to the film and its distribution, obtaining a court order to delay its release and labelling it \"defamatory\".<ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-18/news-interviews/28230561_1_doon-short-film-ashvin|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The DVD sales on campus were immediately halted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-School-bans-Ashvin-Kumars-film/articleshow/6919672.cms|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=ex-student-film>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701125916/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 July 2012|title=Ex-student's film celebrating Doon draws school's ire|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 December 2010}}</ref> The dispute  remains unresolved between the director and school authorities. On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Present day====\nIn June 2016, the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin as headmaster. Until the start of McLaughlin's headmastership, the student demographic was dominated by boys hailing from the [[North Indian]] states. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's outreach initiative of inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian|South]] and [[Northeast India|Northeast Indian]] states.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school occupies a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. \n\n===Architecture===\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received an \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe Chandbagh estate is located adjacent to [[Dehradun Cantonment]] in the green zone of [[Dehradun]], and a wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on the estate, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the Forest Research Institute.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/doon-schools-etp-may-be-trendsetter/428364/ |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus, known as Chandbagh.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), where new students live for a year before moving to one of the main houses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Boys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses.\n\nEach housemaster and housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support.\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main Building of the school which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-07-04/special-report/27149351_1_education-system-elite-schools-vikram-seth |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: Spring, Summer and Autumn. New pupils (\"D-Formers or 7th Graders\") join Doon at the beginning of April.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> The Autumn Term runs from August to the year-end examinations in November after which the boys are promoted to the new class beginning in February. These internal examinations are known as \"trials\", while examinations leading to certificates such as the [[Indian School Certificate]] are known as \"finals\". Discipline at the school has always been strict, and the school has expelled children from well-known families. In the 1950s, Martyn's suggestion that [[Sanjay Gandhi]] finish his senior year elsewhere was accepted without question by his mother, Indira Gandhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20081202/dplus1.htm |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2014 Dehradun Plus |work=The Tribune |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> \n\nSocial work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]] the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>  \n\n===School songs===\nThe school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School Prayer book p.02-26</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's Song Book, which includes: ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]]; ''[[Saare Jahan Se Achcha]]'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal; ''Vandana Ke in Swaron Mein'' (a [[Bhajan|bhajan]]); ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]); ''Pitu Matu Sahayak'' (a bhajan); ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the School Song in 1935, fifteen years before it was adopted as India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at Doon.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory for pupils. The school has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket and hockey dominate the sports calendar in spring term, while football, athletics and boxing are played in autumn term. Other sports such as tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics are played all-year round. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium, yoga studio, and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks. In 2014, the school inaugurated a shooting range on campus. Golf is offered to boys in partnership with local golf courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref> Doon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school tournament that draws all major school basketball teams of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/features/the-asian-school-bag-bball-trophy-233461 |title=The Asian School bag b\u2019ball trophy |publisher=The Tribune India |date=2016-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys visit other schools and academies from time to time to take part in various tournaments. For skill improvement, the school often invites professional sports bodies to hold training camps, which are usually open to students from across India. In 2013, a football coaching camp was held in association with Bar\u00e7a Academy, the official training school of [[FC Barcelona]],<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/f-c-barcelona-at-doon-july-2013/</ref> and in January 2015, coaches from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] held a week-long cricket training camp on the school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchvision.com/exclusive-inside-mcc-lords-club-india-coaching-camp-drills |title=Live Local Matches &#124; Tips & Techniques &#124; Articles & Podcasts |publisher=PitchVision |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=September_2015&Section=Boarding_Schools&Article=India%27s_best_boys_boarding_school</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon. It is produced by the boys and distributed every Saturday morning.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life.  There are around 70-80 clubs and societies, including astronomy, business, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], quiz, photography and film, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], robotics, paper recycling, weather reporting, pottery, carpentry, [[amateur radio]] and birdwatching, among others.<ref>{{cite web|author=\" + arr[2] + \" |url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412 |title=Premium schools |publisher=Outlook Business |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nBoys can write for, or join the editorial board of, a number of school magazines that are published in English or Hindi. ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication and the official school newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/34/42/obituary/ |title=OBITUARY : Himalayan Journal vol.34/42 |publisher=Himalayanclub.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Distributed every Saturday morning, and edited by pupils, it chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative, political or humorous writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the school community as well as Old Boys, and include satire and criticism of school policies. More subversive publications, critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other magazines include ''The Yearbook'', a heavily illustrated publication for recording all highlights of the school year, and ''The Doon School Information Review'' for cultural criticism. Specialist publications by academic departments include '' Vibgyor'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys take a one-week \"midterm\"&nbsp;\u2013 a rugged trip, often through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents, cooking their own food and hiking. They plan these trips themselves. Alumni have credited these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nDoon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] and alumni such as [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nSome of these expeditions have had their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth has been claimed to hold the high-altitude record for smoking a pipe, which he did on the summit of [[Kamet]] after the first ascent in 1931.<ref name=\"Harish Kapadia\"> {{cite book |last1=Kapadia |first1=Harish |title=Across Peaks and Passes in Garhwal Himalaya |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Across_Peaks_Passes_in_Garhwal_Himalaya.html?id=KptmxrqhKl4C |date=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |location=London |language=English |isbn=9788173870972 |page=17 |quote=The peak of Kamet was attempted several times and finally in 1931 Frank Smythe and Eric Shipton reached the summit along with some others. R.L. Holdsworth, who was with them, smoked a pipe on the summit, which I believe still remains a height record for smokers.}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001 a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002 the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}} 2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/04/11/stories/2002041100070300.htm |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/lf/2002/03/30/stories/2002033000930200.htm |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its Platinum Jubilee, the school launched a music album called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-and-interviews/28261521_1_music-album-doscos-alumni |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The school choir sang two songs (\"Lab pe Aati Hai Dua\" and \"Anand Loke\") for the project but only the former was included in the final recording. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\" />\n\n==Affiliations==\n\n===Ties with other schools===\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became Principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Several families who send their sons to Doon send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> Doon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-24/special-report/28263544_1_doon-school-ipsc-sainik-schools |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Memberships===\nThe Doon School is a member of following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Interact Club|Rotary International's Interact Club]], [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=38&filter_data7=&filter_data10=INDIA&filter_data13=&filter_data15=&key=&submit=SEARCH |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examinations]], [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO)]], Indian Public Schools' Conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802223143/http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |title=Indian Public Schools' Conference |publisher=Ipsc.co.in |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)]], [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the School on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\". The dispute remains unresolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-path-not-taken/article2924231.ece|title=The path not taken|first=Sudhish|last=Kamath|date=23 February 2012|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The documentary was produced in association with the [[British Council]]. Its main purpose was to show the school where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the all-round experience of an Indian residential school. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Huang |first1=Guiyou |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Asian American Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Greenwood_Encyclopedia_of_Asian_Amer.html?id=d5RxDwAAQBAJ |date=2009 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |language= |isbn=9781567207361 |page=860 |quote=...as a boarder at the prestigious Doon School, known as \"the Eton of India\" on Dehradun. Whilst at school, Seth encountered abuse and bullying from many of his fellow classmates, an experience that he later evokes by the character Tapan, the youngest of the Chaterjees, in ''A Suitable Boy''.}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Damrosch |first1=David |title=How to Read World Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/How_to_Read_World_Literature.html?id=1VYsDwAAQBAJ |date=2017 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Son]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781119009245 |page=172 |quote=Chekhov and Zulu became ''Star Trek'' devotees while still in school in India...Significantly, they are enrolled in the Doon School, an elite British-style academy established in the waning years of British Raj.}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" due to the fact that the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bond |first1=Ruskin |title=Strangers in the Night |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Strangers_on_the_Roof.html?id=58nqMgEACAAJ |date=1994 |publisher=[[Penguin Books India]] |location= |language= |isbn=9780140240658 |page=4 |quote=William and Jai did not trail me to this place, as it was a little lowbrow for them (William being Swiss and Jai being Doon School.}}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://raifilm.org.uk/films/doon-school-chronicles/|title=Film : \u201cDoon School Chronicles\u201d \u2013 RAI Ethnographic Film Catalogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School alumni}}\n[[File:Rahul Gandhi at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Rahul Gandhi]] (Class of 1988), Indian politician, [[Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha]] speaking at The Doon School Model United Nations' Conference in August 2017.]]\n\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Pupils of Doon have gone on to achieve prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\" /><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> They include nine [[Union Cabinet of India|Cabinet Ministers]], two [[chief minister]]s, several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]]; nineteen generals, two admirals, former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces and twenty-four ambassadors, including those from India, Pakistan, Nepal and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/06/01/stories/2009060153270700.htm |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was educated at Doon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/magazine/mrs-gandhi-grooms-another-son.html|title=Mrs. Gandhi Grooms Another Son|first=Michael T.|last=Kaufman|date=13 June 1982|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|thumb|left|160px|[[Bunker Roy]], Social activist and the founder of [[Barefoot College]], [[Tilonia]].]]\nNotable Doon alumni to have held senior positions in Indian and Pakistani politics include the former Indian diplomat turned politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], currently a Rajya Sabha nominee, the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], politician [[Kamal Nath]], [[Rahul Gandhi]], [[Sanjay Gandhi]], [[Chief Minister of Odisha ]]  politician [[Naveen Patnaik]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]], politican and poet [[Karan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930/ |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> In the field of literature and poetry, Doon alumni include novelists [[Amitav Ghosh]], [[Vikram Seth]], historian [[Ramachandra Guha]], and [[Ardashir Vakil]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/microsoft-s-new-boss-is-a-window-on-a-better-school-system-9115621.html|title=Microsoft\u2019s new boss is a window on a better school system|date=7 February 2014|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon alumni in journalism include [[Prannoy Roy]], [[Aroon Purie]], [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chandra |first=Ram |url=http://www.careers360.com/news/3632-Aroon-Purie-Editor-in-Chief-India-Today |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124094457/http://www.careers360.com/news/3632-Aroon-Purie-Editor-in-Chief-India-Today |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 November 2009 |title=Aroon Purie on Education |journal=Careers 360 News Magazine |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012 }}</ref> The first Indian [[Rhodes scholar]] was a Doon School alumni - [[Lovraj Kumar]].<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon is also the alma mater of the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, [[Abhinav Bindra]] and the mountaineering pioneer [[Nandu Jayal]].<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Anish Kapoor at the Deutsche Guggenheim - Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|160px|[[Anish Kapoor]] is a sculptor whose designs include [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]].<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/>]] In the field of arts and entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Ali Fazal]], [[Roshan Seth]], [[Himani Shivpuri]], [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]] and [[Abhishek Poddar]], a prominent art collector.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/article2890613.ece |title=A Renaissance Woman|newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Turner Prize]]-winning sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> In business, the Doon alumni include [[Analjit Singh]] of Max Group, [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], chairman of [[Hero MotoCorp]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref>  [[Anil Kumar]], former senior partner at [[McKinsey & Company]] and co-founder of the [[Indian School of Business]], [[Gautam Thapar]], founder and chairman of the [[Avantha Group]], [[Malvinder Mohan Singh]] and [[Shivinder Mohan Singh]], former owners of [[Fortis Healthcare]], [[Ajay S. Shriram]], managing director of [[DCM Shriram group]] and [[Sharan Pasricha]], CEO of Ennismore hospitality developer and founder of [[The Hoxton]] and [[Gleneagles Hotel|Gleneagles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/gleneagles-is-a-sleeping-giant-well-make-it-the-best-hotel-in-the-world-lbhjf75z0|title=\u2018Gleneagles is a sleeping giant. We\u2019ll make it the best hotel in the world\u2019|first=Dominic|last=Walsh|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/IN/XNSE/DCMSHRIRAM/company-people/executive-profile/10062|title=DCMSHRIRAM.IN Company Profile & Executives - DCM Shriram Ltd. - Wall Street Journal|website=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nIn the early years, many teachers came from British schools, including [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]] from Eton College,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] from [[Ripon Grammar School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]] and [[R. L. Holdsworth]] from Harrow.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The school's first art teacher was the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]], from [[Visva-Bharati University|Shantiniketan]], who joined in 1936 and remained at school for twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Many sculptures and murals on the campus today were created by him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jnaf.org/artist/sudhir-khastgir/|title=Sudhir Khastgir - JNAF}}</ref> The film director [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]] taught briefly at the school from 1940 to 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/dev-anand-chetan-anand-doon-school-dehradun/story/1/19703.html|title=How Doon School inspired the inimitable Dev Anand style|website=www.dailyo.in}}</ref> Mountaineer [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] joined in 1946 as a geography teacher and led the boys on many expeditions.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/50-years-later-its-happily-Everest-after/articleshow/46893756.cms|title=50 years later, it's happily Everest after &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The cricketer and mathematics teacher, [[Sheel Vohra]], joined in 1959 and became the longest-serving master in school's history when he retired in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/remembering-sheel-vohra-doon-schools-beloved-bond.html|title=Remembering Sheel Vohra, Doon School's beloved 'Bond'|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> The [[Fiji-Indian]] academic [[Satendra Nandan]] taught history at school in the early 1960s, and the [[sarod]] player [[Ashok Roy]] headed the music department from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Popular science]] author and theoretical physicist, [[Simon Singh]], taught science at Doon in 1987 before embarking on his academic and writing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010 {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], IPSS (1985) edited by Sumer Singh, published by the Indian Public Schools Society 1985. ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''],  a periodic newsletter by the Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, published by [[Routledge]] 1998 {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "CallMeByYourMane", "label": "safe", "comment": "correct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Doon_School"}
{"title_page": "Association for the Taxation of Financial Transactions and for Citizens' Action", "text_new": "{{short description|French tax advocacy group}}\n{{Infobox non-profit\n| name              = ATTAC\n| image             = [[Image:Attac logo.png|225px|logo of ATTAC]]\n| type              = [[Voluntary association]]\n| founded_date      = {{Start date and age|1998|June|3|df=y}}\n| tax_id            = \n| registration_id   =\n| founder           = \n| location          = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins           = A [[single-issue movement]] that was founded in France after [[Ignacio Ramonet]] published an editorial in ''[[Le Monde diplomatique]]'' that read \u00ab Disarm the markets<ref name=\"Disarming the markets\">[[Ignacio Ramonet]], [http://mondediplo.com/1997/12/leader Disarming the markets], ''[[Le Monde diplomatique]]'', December 1997.</ref> \u00bb. Supporters founded an association to promote the [[Tobin tax]].\n| key_people        = \n| area_served       = worldwide\n| product           = \n| mission           = International movement working towards social, environmental and democratic alternatives in the [[globalisation]] process.\n| focus             = \n| method            = [[Popular education]], [[meetings]], [[Academic conference|conferences]], [[counter-arguments]] [[documents]] \n| revenue           = \n| endowment         = \n| num_volunteers    = \n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       = {{formatnum:90000}}\n| subsid            = \n| opponents         = \n| owner             = \n| non-profit_slogan = \"Another World is possible\"\n| former name       =\n| homepage          = [https://www.attac.org/ www.attac.org]\n| dissolved         = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n[[Image:Countries-Attac.png|thumb|Countries or jurisdictions that have ATTAC branches]]<!--Quebec in Canada is not a country  -->\n[[Image:ATTAC poster Ameugny 200409.jpg|thumb|An ATTAC poster in the French countryside, 2004]]\n[[Image:Attac1.jpg|thumb|An ATTAC [[banner]] in front of [[Cologne Cathedral]], [[Germany]], 2004]]\n[[Image:Manif Paris 2005-11-19 dsc06338.jpg|thumb|French ATTAC members protesting privatisation and the \"dismantling\" of public services, 2005]]\n[[Image:%attac.JPG|thumb|An ATTAC stall at the ''Volksstimmefest'', [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], 2005 ([[:Image:%attac.JPG|details]])]]\nThe '''Association pour la Taxation des Transactions financi\u00e8res et pour l'Action Citoyenne''' ('''''Association for the Taxation of financial Transactions and Citizen's Action''''', '''ATTAC''') is an activist organisation originally created to promote the establishment of a tax on [[Foreign exchange market|foreign exchange]] transactions.\n\n==Background==\nOriginally called \"Action for a Tobin Tax to Assist the Citizen\", ATTAC was a [[single-issue movement]] demanding the introduction of the so-called [[Tobin tax]] on [[currency]] [[speculation]].<ref name=Moberg>[On the ATTAC: A new European alternative to globalisation, David Moberg, These Times magazine, May 2001]</ref> ATTAC has enlarged its scope to a wide range of issues related to [[globalisation]], and monitoring the decisions of the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO), the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD,) and the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF). ATTAC representatives attend the meetings of the [[G8]] with the goal of influencing policymakers' decisions. Attac spokesmen recently criticised [[Germany]] for what it called the criminalisation of anti-G8 groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/EFC22DAF-E4DF-4E86-A850-0D3E2F67E81C.htm |title=German police raid G8 opponents |accessdate=2007-05-10| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070512012829/http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/EFC22DAF-E4DF-4E86-A850-0D3E2F67E81C.htm| archivedate= 12 May 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAt the founding, ATTAC had specific statutory objectives based on the promotion of the Tobin tax. For example, ATTAC [[Luxembourg]] specifies in article 1 of its statutes that it \n<blockquote>\"aims to produce and communicate information, and to promote and carry out activities of all kinds for the recapture, by the citizens, of the power that the financial sector has on all aspects of political, economic, social and cultural life throughout the world. Such means include the taxation of transactions in foreign exchange markets (Tobin tax).\"<ref name=LLUX>[http://www.etat.lu/memorial/2000/C/Pdf/c0470047.pdf#Page=42 ''Luxembourg Official Journal'', p. 42, ATTAC Statutes (Translated from French)]</ref></blockquote>\n\nATTAC refutes claims that it is an [[anti-globalisation movement]], but it criticises the [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal ideology]] that it sees as dominating economic globalisation. It supports those globalisation policies that their representatives characterise as [[Sustainable development|sustainable]] and [[Social justice|socially just]].<ref name=Moberg /> One of ATTAC's slogans is \"The World is not for sale\", denouncing the \"[[Merchandization|merchandisation]]\" of society. Another slogan is \"Another world is possible\", pointing to an alternative globalisation in which people and not profit is in focus.\n\n===James Tobin opposing ATTAC===\nAttac was founded to promote the [[Tobin tax]] by the [[Keynesian]] economist [[James Tobin]]. Tobin has said that Attac has misused his name. He says he has nothing in common with their goals and supports [[free trade]] \u2014 \"everything that these movements are attacking. They're misusing my name.\" <ref name=spiegel>[http://www.econ.yale.edu/news/tobin/jt_01-09-02_ds_misusing-name.htm \"They Are Misusing My Name\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928082207/http://www.econ.yale.edu/news/tobin/jt_01-09-02_ds_misusing-name.htm |date=September 28, 2011 }}, an interview with James Tobin, ''Der Spiegel'', 03 September 2001</ref>\n\n==Organisational history==\nIn December 1997, [[Ignacio Ramonet]] wrote in ''[[Le Monde diplomatique]]'' an editorial<ref name=\"Disarming the markets\"/> in which he advocated the establishment of the [[Tobin tax]] and the creation of an organisation to pressure governments around the world to introduce the tax.  ATTAC was created on June 3, 1998, during a constitutive assembly in [[France]].  While it was founded in France it now exists in over forty countries around the world.<ref>[http://www.attac.org/about/map ATTAC chapters around the world]</ref>  In France, politicians from the left  are members of the association. {{Citation needed|date=February 2009}}  In Luxembourg, [[Francois Bausch]] of the left Green party is the founding politician in the association's initial member list.<ref name=LLUX />\n\nATTAC functions on a principle of [[decentralisation]]: local associations organise meetings, conferences, and compose documents that become counter-arguments to the perceived neoliberal discourse. ATTAC aims to formalise the possibility of an alternative to the neoliberal society that is currently required of globalisation. ATTAC aspires to be a movement of popular education.\n\n==Views on Attac and its members in different countries==\n\n=== Finland ===\nCommunist [[Juhani Lohikoski]], previously a chairman of [[Communist Youth League]] and [[Socialist League (Finland)|Socialist League]], served as the chairman of Finnish Attac for two terms (2002 - 2004). [[Yrj\u00f6 Hakanen]], chairman of the [[Communist Party of Finland (1997)|Communist Party of Finland]], was a member of the board and a member of the founding committee. In March 2002 [[Aimo Kairamo]], the long-time chief editor of the party organ of the Social Democrat Party, resigned from Attac and recommended the same decision for other social democrats because of the left-wing minority communists' leading positions. Soon also the social democrat foreign minister [[Erkki Tuomioja]] considered to follow Kairamo's example.<ref>[http://www.mtv3.fi/uutiset/arkisto.shtml/arkistot/kotimaa/2002/04/107087 Tuomioja eroaa Attacista?] MTV3.fi, 03.04.2002</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nResearcher Malin Gawell covers the birth and development of Attac Sweden in her doctoral thesis on activist entrepreneurship. She suggests that Attac in Sweden was formed by people seeking a new way of organising with flat hierarchy, and with the strongly sensed need of making a change as the driving force.<ref>[http://su.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:189996/FULLTEXT01 Gawell, Malin (2006). Activist entrepreneurship: attac'ing norms and articulating disclosive stories. Diss. Stockholm : Stockholms universitet, 2007]</ref>\n<br />\nFrom another perspective, [[Sydsvenskan]] newspaper suggested that the downturn of memberships in Swedish Attac after the hype in the beginning of 2001 may be due to its views on trade policies.<ref name=syds191>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071006032639/http://sydsvenskan.se/opinion/huvudledare/article57740.ece Det goda livet], [[Sydsvenskan]], p\u00e4\u00e4kirjoitus 19.1.2004</ref>\n\n==Issues and activities==\nThe main issues covered by ATTAC today are:{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* Control of financial markets (e.g., Tobin tax)\n* \"Fair\" instead of \"free\" trade, via democratic control of the [[World Trade Organization]] and international financial institutions such the [[International Monetary Fund]], [[Worldbank]], [[European Union]], [[North American Free Trade Agreement]], [[Free Trade Area of the Americas]], and [[G8]].\n* Defense of public goods - air, water, information\n* Defense of public social services - like those relevant to health, social services, and [[social security]].  For example, it is against the [[privatisation]] of [[pension]]s and of the [[health care system]].  ATTAC has also taken a position on genetically modified organisms.  ATTAC also opposes [[General Agreement on Trade in Services]].\n* The struggle to end tax evasion ([[corporate haven|tax havens]]) as practiced by transnational corporations and rich individuals\n* Sustainable globalisation\n* Cancellation of the [[debt of Developing Countries]].\n* ATTAC campaigned against the [[Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe]].\n* ATTAC is involved in fighting against [[climate change]], for [[environmental justice]] and, especially, in supporting [[Alternatiba, Village of Alternatives]].\n\nIn France, ATTAC associates with many other [[left-wing]] causes.\n\n==Nestl\u00e9gate==\nIn the year 2008 Attac [[Switzerland]] was hit by a scandal which was later called Nestl\u00e9gate by the local media. Between the years 2003 and 2005, the Swiss multinational food and beverage company [[Nestl\u00e9]], engaged the external Security company [[Securitas AG]], to spy on the Swiss Attac branch. Nestl\u00e9 started the monitoring, when Attac Switzerland decided to work on a critical book about Nestl\u00e9.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Klawitter|first1=Nils|title=Spitzel-Aff\u00e4re um Nestl\u00e9|url=http://www.spiegel.de/wirtschaft/unternehmen/spitzel-affaere-um-nestle-das-war-klassisches-profiling-a-811608.html|accessdate=6 April 2015|publisher=Spiegel.de|date=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nDue to Nestl\u00e9gate, Attac Switzerland filed a lawsuit against Nestl\u00e9 which was decided in favour of Attac in January 2013, as the personal rights of the observed were violated. They received a compensation for damages of 3'000 [[Swiss francs]] each, which has an equivalent of about 3'230 USD at the date of the proclamation of sentence.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Attac Schweiz |title=Nestl\u00e9gate: Voller Erfolg im Zivilprozess gegen Nestl\u00e9 und Securitas |url=http://www.attac-netzwerk.de/das-netzwerk/internationales/die-ag-internationales/regionen/europa/schweiz/20130125-attac-schweiz-nestlegate/ |website=Attac Netzwerk |accessdate=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411123451/http://www.attac-netzwerk.de/das-netzwerk/internationales/die-ag-internationales/regionen/europa/schweiz/20130125-attac-schweiz-nestlegate/ |archivedate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alter-globalisation]]\n* [[Anti-globalisation]]\n* [[Clearstream]] scandal, a [[clearing house (finance)|clearing house]] (meta-bank) involved in one of the biggest financial scandals ever\n* [[Currency transaction tax]]\n* [[Financial transaction tax]]\n* [[Global financial system]]\n* [[MRAP (French NGO)|MRAP]], anti-racist NGO engaged in the creation of ATTAC\n* [[Robin Hood tax]]\n* [[Tobin tax]]\n* [[Ireland as a tax haven]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{Cite journal | last = Cassen | first = Bernard (interviewee) | author-link = Bernard Cassen | title = On the attack | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 19 | pages = 41\u201360 | publisher = New Left Review | date = January\u2013February 2003 | url = http://newleftreview.org/II/19/bernard-cassen-on-the-attack | language = English | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\n* {{Cite journal | last = Cassen | first = Bernard | title = Attack against the treaty | author-link = Bernard Cassen | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 33 | pages = 27\u201333 | publisher = New Left Review | date = May\u2013June 2005 | url = https://newleftreview.org/II/33/bernard-cassen-attac-against-the-treaty | language = English | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|ATTAC}}\n* [https://www.attac.org/en ATTAC official web site]\n* [https://mondediplo.com/1997/12/leader \"Disarming the Markets\"], editorial by [[Ignacio Ramonet]]\n* {{Cite journal | last = Cassen | first = Bernard | title = Attack against the treaty | author-link = Bernard Cassen | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 33 | pages = 27\u201333 | publisher = New Left Review | date = May\u2013June 2005 | url = https://newleftreview.org/II/33/bernard-cassen-attac-against-the-treaty | language = English | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Association Pour La Taxation Des Transactions Pour L'aide Aux Citoyens}}\n[[Category:Anti-globalization organizations]]\n[[Category:Political and economic think tanks based in France]]\n[[Category:Tax reform]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Financial transaction tax]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French tax advocacy group}}\n{{Infobox non-profit\n| name              = ATTAC\n| image             = [[Image:Attac logo.png|225px|logo of ATTAC]]\n| type              = [[Voluntary association]]\n| founded_date      = {{Start date and age|1998|June|3|df=y}}\n| tax_id            = \n| registration_id   =\n| founder           = \n| location          = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins           = A [[single-issue movement]] that was founded in France after [[Ignacio Ramonet]] published an editorial in ''[[Le Monde diplomatique]]''entitled \u00ab Disarm the markets<ref name=\"Disarming the markets\">[[Ignacio Ramonet]], [http://mondediplo.com/1997/12/leader Disarming the markets], ''[[Le Monde diplomatique]]'', December 1997.</ref> \u00bb. Supporters founded an association to promote the [[Tobin tax]].\n| key_people        = \n| area_served       = worldwide\n| product           = \n| mission           = International movement working towards social, environmental and democratic alternatives in the [[globalisation]] process.\n| focus             = \n| method            = [[Popular education]], [[meetings]], [[Academic conference|conferences]], [[counter-arguments]] [[documents]] \n| revenue           = \n| endowment         = \n| num_volunteers    = \n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       = {{formatnum:90000}}\n| subsid            = \n| opponents         = \n| owner             = \n| non-profit_slogan = \"Another World is possible\"\n| former name       =\n| homepage          = [https://www.attac.org/ www.attac.org]\n| dissolved         = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n[[Image:Countries-Attac.png|thumb|Countries or jurisdictions that have ATTAC branches]]<!--Quebec in Canada is not a country  -->\n[[Image:ATTAC poster Ameugny 200409.jpg|thumb|An ATTAC poster in the French countryside, 2004]]\n[[Image:Attac1.jpg|thumb|An ATTAC [[banner]] in front of [[Cologne Cathedral]], [[Germany]], 2004]]\n[[Image:Manif Paris 2005-11-19 dsc06338.jpg|thumb|French ATTAC members protesting privatisation and the \"dismantling\" of public services, 2005]]\n[[Image:%attac.JPG|thumb|An ATTAC stall at the ''Volksstimmefest'', [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], 2005 ([[:Image:%attac.JPG|details]])]]\nThe '''Association pour la Taxation des Transactions financi\u00e8res et pour l'Action Citoyenne''' ('''''Association for the Taxation of financial Transactions and Citizen's Action''''', '''ATTAC''') is an activist organisation originally created to promote the establishment of a tax on [[Foreign exchange market|foreign exchange]] transactions.\n\n==Background==\nOriginally called \"Action for a Tobin Tax to Assist the Citizen\", ATTAC was a [[single-issue movement]] demanding the introduction of the so-called [[Tobin tax]] on [[currency]] [[speculation]].<ref name=Moberg>[On the ATTAC: A new European alternative to globalisation, David Moberg, These Times magazine, May 2001]</ref> ATTAC has enlarged its scope to a wide range of issues related to [[globalisation]], and monitoring the decisions of the [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO), the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD,) and the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF). ATTAC representatives attend the meetings of the [[G8]] with the goal of influencing policymakers' decisions. Attac spokesmen recently criticised [[Germany]] for what it called the criminalisation of anti-G8 groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/EFC22DAF-E4DF-4E86-A850-0D3E2F67E81C.htm |title=German police raid G8 opponents |accessdate=2007-05-10| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070512012829/http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/EFC22DAF-E4DF-4E86-A850-0D3E2F67E81C.htm| archivedate= 12 May 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAt the founding, ATTAC had specific statutory objectives based on the promotion of the Tobin tax. For example, ATTAC [[Luxembourg]] specifies in article 1 of its statutes that it \n<blockquote>\"aims to produce and communicate information, and to promote and carry out activities of all kinds for the recapture, by the citizens, of the power that the financial sector has on all aspects of political, economic, social and cultural life throughout the world. Such means include the taxation of transactions in foreign exchange markets (Tobin tax).\"<ref name=LLUX>[http://www.etat.lu/memorial/2000/C/Pdf/c0470047.pdf#Page=42 ''Luxembourg Official Journal'', p. 42, ATTAC Statutes (Translated from French)]</ref></blockquote>\n\nATTAC refutes claims that it is an [[anti-globalisation movement]], but it criticises the [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal ideology]] that it sees as dominating economic globalisation. It supports those globalisation policies that their representatives characterise as [[Sustainable development|sustainable]] and [[Social justice|socially just]].<ref name=Moberg /> One of ATTAC's slogans is \"The World is not for sale\", denouncing the \"[[Merchandization|merchandisation]]\" of society. Another slogan is \"Another world is possible\", pointing to an alternative globalisation in which people and not profit is in focus.\n\n===James Tobin opposing ATTAC===\nAttac was founded to promote the [[Tobin tax]] by the [[Keynesian]] economist [[James Tobin]]. Tobin has said that Attac has misused his name. He says he has nothing in common with their goals and supports [[free trade]] \u2014 \"everything that these movements are attacking. They're misusing my name.\" <ref name=spiegel>[http://www.econ.yale.edu/news/tobin/jt_01-09-02_ds_misusing-name.htm \"They Are Misusing My Name\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928082207/http://www.econ.yale.edu/news/tobin/jt_01-09-02_ds_misusing-name.htm |date=September 28, 2011 }}, an interview with James Tobin, ''Der Spiegel'', 03 September 2001</ref>\n\n==Organisational history==\nIn December 1997, [[Ignacio Ramonet]] wrote in ''[[Le Monde diplomatique]]'' an editorial<ref name=\"Disarming the markets\"/> in which he advocated the establishment of the [[Tobin tax]] and the creation of an organisation to pressure governments around the world to introduce the tax.  ATTAC was created on June 3, 1998, during a constitutive assembly in [[France]].  While it was founded in France it now exists in over forty countries around the world.<ref>[http://www.attac.org/about/map ATTAC chapters around the world]</ref>  In France, politicians from the left  are members of the association. {{Citation needed|date=February 2009}}  In Luxembourg, [[Francois Bausch]] of the left Green party is the founding politician in the association's initial member list.<ref name=LLUX />\n\nATTAC functions on a principle of [[decentralisation]]: local associations organise meetings, conferences, and compose documents that become counter-arguments to the perceived neoliberal discourse. ATTAC aims to formalise the possibility of an alternative to the neoliberal society that is currently required of globalisation. ATTAC aspires to be a movement of popular education.\n\n==Views on Attac and its members in different countries==\n\n=== Finland ===\nCommunist [[Juhani Lohikoski]], previously a chairman of [[Communist Youth League]] and [[Socialist League (Finland)|Socialist League]], served as the chairman of Finnish Attac for two terms (2002 - 2004). [[Yrj\u00f6 Hakanen]], chairman of the [[Communist Party of Finland (1997)|Communist Party of Finland]], was a member of the board and a member of the founding committee. In March 2002 [[Aimo Kairamo]], the long-time chief editor of the party organ of the Social Democrat Party, resigned from Attac and recommended the same decision for other social democrats because of the left-wing minority communists' leading positions. Soon also the social democrat foreign minister [[Erkki Tuomioja]] considered to follow Kairamo's example.<ref>[http://www.mtv3.fi/uutiset/arkisto.shtml/arkistot/kotimaa/2002/04/107087 Tuomioja eroaa Attacista?] MTV3.fi, 03.04.2002</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nResearcher Malin Gawell covers the birth and development of Attac Sweden in her doctoral thesis on activist entrepreneurship. She suggests that Attac in Sweden was formed by people seeking a new way of organising with flat hierarchy, and with the strongly sensed need of making a change as the driving force.<ref>[http://su.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:189996/FULLTEXT01 Gawell, Malin (2006). Activist entrepreneurship: attac'ing norms and articulating disclosive stories. Diss. Stockholm : Stockholms universitet, 2007]</ref>\n<br />\nFrom another perspective, [[Sydsvenskan]] newspaper suggested that the downturn of memberships in Swedish Attac after the hype in the beginning of 2001 may be due to its views on trade policies.<ref name=syds191>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071006032639/http://sydsvenskan.se/opinion/huvudledare/article57740.ece Det goda livet], [[Sydsvenskan]], p\u00e4\u00e4kirjoitus 19.1.2004</ref>\n\n==Issues and activities==\nThe main issues covered by ATTAC today are:{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* Control of financial markets (e.g., Tobin tax)\n* \"Fair\" instead of \"free\" trade, via democratic control of the [[World Trade Organization]] and international financial institutions such the [[International Monetary Fund]], [[Worldbank]], [[European Union]], [[North American Free Trade Agreement]], [[Free Trade Area of the Americas]], and [[G8]].\n* Defense of public goods - air, water, information\n* Defense of public social services - like those relevant to health, social services, and [[social security]].  For example, it is against the [[privatisation]] of [[pension]]s and of the [[health care system]].  ATTAC has also taken a position on genetically modified organisms.  ATTAC also opposes [[General Agreement on Trade in Services]].\n* The struggle to end tax evasion ([[corporate haven|tax havens]]) as practiced by transnational corporations and rich individuals\n* Sustainable globalisation\n* Cancellation of the [[debt of Developing Countries]].\n* ATTAC campaigned against the [[Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe]].\n* ATTAC is involved in fighting against [[climate change]], for [[environmental justice]] and, especially, in supporting [[Alternatiba, Village of Alternatives]].\n\nIn France, ATTAC associates with many other [[left-wing]] causes.\n\n==Nestl\u00e9gate==\nIn the year 2008 Attac [[Switzerland]] was hit by a scandal which was later called Nestl\u00e9gate by the local media. Between the years 2003 and 2005, the Swiss multinational food and beverage company [[Nestl\u00e9]], engaged the external Security company [[Securitas AG]], to spy on the Swiss Attac branch. Nestl\u00e9 started the monitoring, when Attac Switzerland decided to work on a critical book about Nestl\u00e9.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Klawitter|first1=Nils|title=Spitzel-Aff\u00e4re um Nestl\u00e9|url=http://www.spiegel.de/wirtschaft/unternehmen/spitzel-affaere-um-nestle-das-war-klassisches-profiling-a-811608.html|accessdate=6 April 2015|publisher=Spiegel.de|date=2012-01-30}}</ref>\n\nDue to Nestl\u00e9gate, Attac Switzerland filed a lawsuit against Nestl\u00e9 which was decided in favour of Attac in January 2013, as the personal rights of the observed were violated. They received a compensation for damages of 3'000 [[Swiss francs]] each, which has an equivalent of about 3'230 USD at the date of the proclamation of sentence.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Attac Schweiz |title=Nestl\u00e9gate: Voller Erfolg im Zivilprozess gegen Nestl\u00e9 und Securitas |url=http://www.attac-netzwerk.de/das-netzwerk/internationales/die-ag-internationales/regionen/europa/schweiz/20130125-attac-schweiz-nestlegate/ |website=Attac Netzwerk |accessdate=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411123451/http://www.attac-netzwerk.de/das-netzwerk/internationales/die-ag-internationales/regionen/europa/schweiz/20130125-attac-schweiz-nestlegate/ |archivedate=11 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alter-globalisation]]\n* [[Anti-globalisation]]\n* [[Clearstream]] scandal, a [[clearing house (finance)|clearing house]] (meta-bank) involved in one of the biggest financial scandals ever\n* [[Currency transaction tax]]\n* [[Financial transaction tax]]\n* [[Global financial system]]\n* [[MRAP (French NGO)|MRAP]], anti-racist NGO engaged in the creation of ATTAC\n* [[Robin Hood tax]]\n* [[Tobin tax]]\n* [[Ireland as a tax haven]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{Cite journal | last = Cassen | first = Bernard (interviewee) | author-link = Bernard Cassen | title = On the attack | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 19 | pages = 41\u201360 | publisher = New Left Review | date = January\u2013February 2003 | url = http://newleftreview.org/II/19/bernard-cassen-on-the-attack | language = English | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\n* {{Cite journal | last = Cassen | first = Bernard | title = Attack against the treaty | author-link = Bernard Cassen | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 33 | pages = 27\u201333 | publisher = New Left Review | date = May\u2013June 2005 | url = https://newleftreview.org/II/33/bernard-cassen-attac-against-the-treaty | language = English | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|ATTAC}}\n* [https://www.attac.org/en ATTAC official web site]\n* [https://mondediplo.com/1997/12/leader \"Disarming the Markets\"], editorial by [[Ignacio Ramonet]]\n* {{Cite journal | last = Cassen | first = Bernard | title = Attack against the treaty | author-link = Bernard Cassen | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 33 | pages = 27\u201333 